(9, '2018-07-25', 'I can only win', '', 'People ask, &ldquo;What&rsquo;s wrong with you? You can&rsquo;t possibly win a seat on Oconee County Council. They don&rsquo;t want to hear from a Democrat&rdquo; &nbsp;I don&rsquo;t argue. l smile. &nbsp;I can&rsquo;t lose because I will contribute value to the game. <br /><br />&bull; I tell \'em&nbsp;my campaign is a&nbsp;first step&nbsp;in a longer campaign.<br /><br />&bull; I tell &lsquo;em I don&rsquo;t need victory to win.<br /><br />&bull; I tell &lsquo;em I serve all of us, including liberals and progressives who are coming here to live.<br /><br />&bull; I tell &lsquo;em I\'m with&nbsp;conservatives who want conservative politics to change.<br /><br />&bull; I tell &lsquo;em&nbsp;I&rsquo;m a lobbyist for an alternative pov that works for everybody.<br /><br />&bull; I remind them that we must always take a first step and I here to take that step.'),
(10, '2018-07-28', 'Liberal opinion writers need to stop writing about the incumbent', '', 'People who voted for &nbsp;Trump, feel their values - thus themselves - endlessly attacked. &nbsp;Those attacks by liberals are a mistake. &nbsp;Personal attacks do not serve the purposes of people who want change, which includes many conservatives. &nbsp;There are better ways. We are making people angry and that does not help our cause. &nbsp; Look into the methods suggested by the Better Angels movement.<br /><br />Liberal opinion writers must find a new subject. Write about nothing that begins with &ldquo;T&rdquo;. Write only about things that begin with &ldquo;C&rdquo;: &nbsp;Camping, Chiles, China, cold weather, cocoa, etc. &nbsp;The fixation with the White House reminds me of an old axiom about shows, &nbsp;the more the critics damn your show, the more interest they create which is better and cheaper than advertising. Drop personal attacks, discuss issues. Conservatives and liberals ought try coming together to define an immigration law that works for the country.'),
(11, '2018-07-28', 'Save cities with apartments over stores', '', 'I spent some time today driving around Seneca, Oconee&rsquo;s biggest city. We all know its problem; it&rsquo;s a city without people. Shops are closed, empty windows look out onto empty streets. Business has left town for the highways. Without people a city cannot survive.<br /><br />That means Seneca has an opportunity. Put apartments above every store. Design them for everybody including the elderly and the young, for people who need service and for people to serve them. The city could fill empty stores with local businesses that will thrive. Downtown Seneca has transportation, police, space, postal service, sewers and plumbing, electricity and gas. That sounds like a money saving development opportunity.<br /><br />It&rsquo;s a no-brainer. City Council could contact Clemson&rsquo;s school of architecture and consult with faculty. Graduate students could imagine how to develop apartments over the stores in downtown Seneca because people will want to come and live in a pleasant, convenient, and comfortable city center where owning a car is not necessary, where a community will develop overnight, where property owners will thrive once again. Stop tearing up Oconee&rsquo;s forests, develop downtown. <br /><br />Oconee&rsquo;s other cities could do the same thing. Put apartments over stores, rebuild cities.'),
(20, '2018-11-05', 'Claiming Transcendent', '', 'I have struggled for forty years with the way one word is understood.&nbsp; I know <em>transcendent</em> is the appropriate word for me to use, but dictionary definitions do not include my experience. Merriam Webster offers these synonyms: metaphysical, otherworldly, paranormal, unearthly. They declare the opposite&nbsp;meaning of <em>transcendent i</em>s &ldquo;natural.&rdquo; I can\'t accept that. &nbsp;From my experience transcendent is entirely &ldquo;natural.&rdquo;<br /><br />Here&rsquo;s the problem. We humans are wired from birth to learn a social identity. Some call it &ldquo;ego,&rdquo; some call it the &ldquo;Little Self.&rdquo; In Pakistan one learns a social identity fundamentally different from one learned in Alabama. Both are valid, necessary, and tribal. But that social ID is only a fraction of who we really are.<br /><br />Our social identity is a role like any role, but actors drop theirs&rsquo; when the curtain falls. Lay people don&rsquo;t realize they role-play all the time and believe they must live that role, which is only a tribal role. By the time we&rsquo;re about twenty-five, we\'ve come to believe our role totally defines us, as in, I&rsquo;m a white American male, that\'s all, nothing else. It\'s almost like an actor coming to believe he\'s Hamlet. And no school, church, temple, mosque, or nation will teach you otherwise. &nbsp;It would weaken their objectives.<br /><br />But we are more than our role. On some deep, inarticulate level we know that. Which means we need to let go of the&nbsp;<em><u><strong>need</strong>&nbsp;</u>to play that role</em>. Some Pakistanis believe they need to kill daughters who dishonor them. Some Alabamians believe African Americans are less than human. <br />All of those people need to let go of the need to accept those inhumane ideas.<br /><br />Letting go of our <u>attachment&nbsp;</u>to tribal identities defines Buddha&rsquo;s insight. In English buddha means &ldquo;the man who woke up.&rdquo; Jesus urged us &ldquo;to be as children&rdquo; because children had not learned a tribal ID. <br /><br />I grew up conditioned to be a Catholic, by eighteen I had rebelled and began a search to find who I was. I searched every belief system I could find. I used LSD, smoked weed, studied Zen, and much more. I was skeptical of all believers.<br /><br />However, all that searching over 30 years prepared me for one life-changing experience that told me who I am. <br /><br />It happened at my desk. &nbsp;Reading science, I discovered what a star does. For years I -like most people - had wondered, &ldquo;Who am I?&nbsp; Where did I come from?&rdquo;&nbsp; Suddenly, at my desk, I discovered the answer. I am star stuff. We all are. A fact.<br />&nbsp;<br />My molecules and atoms were literally cooked into being out of energy/matter in the heart of a star(s) eons ago before it exploded, casting all my energy/matter into space.&nbsp; Gravity spun that material into a swirling mass that became our sun and planets, and out of Earth&rsquo;s soil all living things emerged.&nbsp; Who am I?&nbsp; An earth man.&nbsp;Where&rsquo;d I come from?&nbsp; The processes of the stars.<br /><br />Social identity no longer defined me, but I couldn&rsquo;t communicate my experience using &ldquo;transcended&rdquo; because people thought it had to mean \"supernatural.\" &nbsp;The word connotes, even defines, the unearthly, the supernatural. <br /><br />I had not transcended Earth. I had transcended \"little me.\" I\'m here, an Earth man beyond tribal restrictions. For one who emerged from Star-stuff the idea of the &ldquo;supernatural&rdquo; is fantasy. <em><u>Testable </u></em>evidence of that idea has never been offered in human history.<br /><br />The realization I am Star-stuff affects my thinking, feelings, reactions, point-of-view, and behavior every day. It allowed me to shed the <u>need&nbsp;</u>for social identity when I discovered that my spiritual roots in Earth&rsquo;s soil make me responsible to Earth and all of Earth&rsquo;s children. That transcends every social identity and defines my purpose as a human being, which is the third questions humans have always asked.&nbsp;<br /><br />I accept my tribal conditioning. I use it, play with it, take advantage of it, but I <strong>do not need it. &nbsp;</strong>All this makes free play easier. &nbsp;It makes our relationship to the words humus (soil?), human, humane, humor and humility much more meaningful.'),
(14, '2018-07-29', 'We have coarsened our culture', '', 'It&rsquo;s apparent from the language we use to the way we dress, we&rsquo;ve coarsened our culture. I&rsquo;ll start with the tattoo fad. Tattoo parlors were illegal 15 years ago in SC. Tattoos were thought coarse. And extreme facial tattoos do express disdain, even dislike for the body we&rsquo;re born with.<br /><br />The list goes on. Except for &ldquo;N&rdquo; and &ldquo;C&rdquo; words, almost all language taboos have gone down the drain with penmanship and spelling. We allow people to use weapons as they please. Stand your ground would have been unimaginable years ago. Now road rage threatens lives. Camouflage clothing, merciless police, fear, toughness rather than gentility, hair high on the side, even shaved heads speak of an unprecedented military influence that coarsens. &nbsp;People can go to upscale restaurants in their underwear. Check out campuses, young women wear cutoff jeans that display the bottoms of their bottoms, males heading to class look like they&rsquo;re going to clean the barn. Formal rules that require good manners and refinement have been dismissed. Crude has become acceptable. Many hold the very idea of refinement in contempt.<br /><br />Women always dressed to attract attention. No problem, but isn&rsquo;t there a perverse relationship here between feminine dress that incites sexual fantasies and the attitudes of the #me too movement? &nbsp;If an attracted man touches her exposed bottom he could get body slammed, as was reported about an incident in a restaurant when a dope thought a barely clothed waitress wanted closer attention. Many young men think bad sexual behavior is funny.<br /><br />Newspapers publish stuff they used to trash. Religious discipline has declined. &nbsp;The great success of Enlightenment thinking in science and scholarship has a shadow side. Data has become its saint, technology its god. Old spiritual traditions are thought of as risible.<br /><br />No wonder MAGA wins hearts and minds. Good manners once facilitated a successful society. Hopefully, we&rsquo;ve almost filled the pit under the seat of our cultural outhouse. Maybe some are planting seeds toward a new cultural ethos. &nbsp;The active students who survived the shootings at Marjory Stoneman Douglas High School raise my hopes for our future.'),
(23, '2018-11-08', 'All Embracing Better Angels', '', 'If I understand the <u>strategy of Better Angels</u>, it is to bring people together interacting with respect.&nbsp;&nbsp;That goal touches upon rampant and evil disrespect, the worst wound in our society. The men and women of Better Angels render a service that must succeed. Until we conquer the uses of &nbsp;scorn and disdain, we will fail to resolve any of our severe social problems.&nbsp;<br /><br />However, I fear some Better Angel tactics could undermine their strategy.<br /><br />For example, using words like &ldquo;partisanship&rdquo; and &ldquo;RED BLUE&rsquo; when describing the mission of Better Angels inevitably limits the BA vision and the recruiting of Independents. Worse, when I talk about \"partisanship\" conservative friends reflect back their own partisanship, suspecting that Better Angles is a liberal program designed to convert conservatives.&nbsp;&nbsp;They&rsquo;re hard to convince otherwise.&nbsp;&nbsp;<u>Moreover&nbsp;</u>many &ndash; who use the internet for purposes other than politics - behave with such intolerable disrespect and derision that their\'s &nbsp;has become almost normal. That is not tolerable in human relations.<br /><br />The most important social need in our time is to restore respect to its proper place in&nbsp;<u>all human interactions</u>. I hope Better Angels will succeed toward that end. Look around the room wherever you are. The techniques and ideas of Better Angels will have proven effective when BA has been embraced by as many men as women, as many African Americans, Hispanic Americans, and Asian Americans as Euro-Americans. Respectful interaction must be practiced by more of us than the agents of the Red and the Blue.<br /><br />My basic position - as a candidate - was to work toward respectful interaction. As a liberal (but not necessarily BLUE and partisan person), I made the specific point that the need to advance learning beyond high school can be met effectively by employing traditional conservative values. My position was met with respect by my opponent.&nbsp; He and I began a cordial relationship. &nbsp;He won, but he has said he would like to consult with me in the future.<br /><br />I believe that kind of political respect can be echoed in all of life&rsquo;s categories.<br />11/10/2018'),
(16, '2018-08-18', 'We Can\'t MAGA, we must evolve a new culture', '', 'I agree with Kentucky&rsquo;s Gov. Bevin that the bad behavior of our people is a cultural problem.<br /><br /><a href=\"http://www.kentuckynewera.com/multimedia/video/news/youtube_c2674705-960f-52ed-b8d8-9d2c34d514e4.html\">http://www.kentuckynewera.com/multimedia/video/news/youtube_c2674705-960f-52ed-b8d8-9d2c34d514e4.html</a><br /><br />He talks about killings with guns. &nbsp;There are also the killings with drugs: 72,000 people in 2017 were killed with drugs, more than with auto accidents. Nothing like that happened in 1950. &nbsp;Why? There has also been a general coarsening of our culture and the Gov mentioned that when he spoke of respect and how respect for the other has been lost in too much of social media, and in other places. &nbsp;The coarsening is evident in dress and language (and yes, I&rsquo;m guilty of leaning into it sometimes, but I didn&rsquo;t do it in 1950.)<br /><br />However, I do not agree with some of his examples. His are examples from a conservative perspective. &nbsp;I&rsquo;m not saying he is wrong, but from my perspective, we cannot MAGA by going back to the fifties we remember and an old ethos that has been exploded, fragmented. &nbsp;The culture will heal or we&rsquo;ll go to war with each other (See Turkey, Poland, Hungary, the Arab lands). &nbsp;We need leadership that does not divide but helps us through the weeds and rough country to evolve a new ethos.<br /><br />Think of this example, the grand jury in Pennsylvania studied abuse by 300 Roman Catholic priests since 1947. &nbsp;I graduated from 12 years of Pennsylvania Catholic schools in 1949. &nbsp;In those twelve years I never heard of, sensed, or imagined sexual predators among the priests I knew and every teacher in my 4 year high school for boys in Chester PA was a Catholic priest. Some of &lsquo;em were tough, even brutal bastards, but I never thought of sex and priests in the same context. &nbsp; The point of my example is the Governor&rsquo;s point, something has happened in the culture since the end of the 40s.<br /><br />In 1919, after the war,&nbsp;William Butler Yeats published, the prophetic poem entitled The Second Coming. The first stanza reads:<br /><br />Turning and turning in the widening gyre<br />The falcon cannot hear the falconer;<br />Things fall apart; the centre cannot hold;<br />Mere anarchy is loosed upon the world,<br />The blood-dimmed tide is loosed, and everywhere<br />The ceremony of innocence is drowned;<br />The best lack all conviction, while the worst<br />Are full of passionate intensity.<br /><br />It is as though he could see into our time. &nbsp;The metphorical something he saw a hundred years ago is evident in many ways. &nbsp;I see it in every aspect of life. &nbsp;The old icons are dead; John Wayne is laughable. &nbsp;The old religious doctrines are dying almost by the year. Hail Mary is a football term. If we believe the data from Pew Research, religion in this country and Euroland is desperate -vide the panic inherent in literal&nbsp;fundamentalism - and on a downward trend. &nbsp;The military and it&rsquo;s methods have become the methods and attitudes of the local cop (maybe not our sheriff). We&rsquo;ve been in constant war for 18 years. &nbsp;Our political leadership has coarsened so much as to permit itself to utter disgusting language on tv.<br /><br />We just came back from two weeks in Santa Cruz. &nbsp;What I saw sharing life with my daughter and her husband was different, made me hopeful. &nbsp;And the difference was rooted in the diversity among the people in their lives and the lives of their friends. &nbsp;The world of color and the human spirit has come to live and mix in CA and a new ethos seems to be evolving there. We attended a Hindu religious service that focused on humane interaction and without rituals.<br /><br />It all felt good, humane, respect full; and filled with possible solutions. &nbsp;Even though traffic on the Interstate moved at 15mph we neither saw nor heard of road rage in two weeks of driving.<br /><br />It&rsquo;s no mass movement yet, but it&rsquo;s a good example of what can evolve.<br /><br />Of course, I should note that CA is Trump&rsquo;s political bete noir.<br /><br />By the way,&nbsp;I believe gun handling should be regulated the same way we regulate automobiles and/or alcohol. &nbsp;BUT the cultural changes make us afraid of one another: the Left fear the Right with the Guns, the Right fear. Period.'),
(24, '2018-11-11', 'On reading Hawking\'s book \"Brief Answers\"', '', 'Just finished <em>Brief Answers.</em><em>&nbsp;</em>Lucy&rsquo;s tribute to her father brought a tear. I admire Hawking&rsquo;s ability to clarify. &nbsp;No one has better clarified Space/Time. &nbsp;I understand the concept clearly at last. &nbsp;I don&rsquo;t quite get his explanation of time travel though, probably because the idea has no appeal to me. &nbsp;Indeed, I don&rsquo;t want to accept the inevitability of Hawking&rsquo;s grim thinking about our future. &nbsp; &nbsp;<br /><br />I find myself beginning to rebel and reject the ever increasing power of digital technology, or the idea Earth&rsquo;s temperature could someday mimic Venus\'. &nbsp;I think some of those postulates serve to alienate people ever more from our place here on Earth as children of the soil. I need to believe that if it is too late to stop the warming of the planet, we will find ways to adapt as we always have. We are <em>of the planet </em>like bees and trees. We are not just passengers on our way to another planet warmed by another star. &nbsp; <br /><br />So, Useful as they are, I&rsquo;m not one who believes STEM programs in the schools are the answer to the grim future predicted by some for the planet and for AI. &nbsp;From my perspective, the domination of the purely rational, technical mind-set goes too far. I can see a time when reaction could set in and be better balanced by the artist/humanist perspective, but I also see few signs of same. &nbsp;Engineers and Techies are trained how to make and run ever more complex tools and things; they&rsquo;re not trained to know the best ways for humanity and Earth to use what they make. &nbsp; &nbsp; <br /><br />Humanity has never rejected the onward march of creating more useful tools from stone axes to nuclear ones, but we are still adolescents when it comes to the best uses of same. Hawking uses the word &ldquo;stupidity.&rdquo; But I like to hope that we adolescents could be on the edge of developing an unprecedented maturity, but to do that we&rsquo;ll have to find out how to continue living fully as Earth&rsquo;s children rather than escaping. &nbsp;I don&rsquo;t want to escape. I&rsquo;d rather go out in the rain. &nbsp;The living critters of Earth and the processes of Earth are too much with me and part of me. &nbsp;We also must make learning to think a school priority. &nbsp;People don&rsquo;t even realize thinking is a skill to learn.<br /><br />Of course, I can imagine a time when our tools take over all our chores and allow us once again to find ourselves as Earth&rsquo;s children and relish our place, our connection to nature and the planet. That would take an emotional maturity we now lack. &nbsp;I like to imagine a time when we can live with wild nature as our ancestors did millennia ago. And keep my car. &nbsp; <br /><br />Marty and I were once driving on CA Route 1 in northern California. &nbsp;&rsquo;Twas a two lane road in a small town when traffic stopped in both directions to allow a herd of elk to cross the road. &nbsp;The animals took their time, grazed on neighbors&rsquo; lawns, disdained the automobiles. &nbsp;Drivers waited patiently until the herd crossed. Some got out of their cars; it didn\'t matter. It was a long, beautiful, engaging moment when we were close, almost intimate with wildlife. I&rsquo;ll never forget it. Now, I hope for a time when a family of wolves will stop traffic on a rural road in the foothills of South Carolina and the people will allow them peaceful passage. &nbsp; <br /><br />So, I have to reject the pessimism I felt while reading Hawking&rsquo;s vision of a tech dominated future. That pessimism got intolerable at one point. I stopped and toyed with the idea that my grandsons&rsquo; generation <em>across the planet</em> ought abstain from breeding. Then I realized how alienated I&rsquo;d become to even give one moment to such a terrible idea.<br />2018-11-14'),
(25, '2018-11-08', 'Hospitals Merge and Patients Pay more NYTimes', '', 'The import of this NYTimes article was strengthened in my mind because of a night I spent suffering in an ER last week. Sufferers must be taken care of by all of us on the spot and fast. Paying for the insurance should not burden &nbsp;employers. &nbsp;Nor should anyone have to shoulder the extreme and sometimes arbitrary fees hospitals feel free to impose. &nbsp;We humans are one. We are a creature with a responsibility to aid each other. &nbsp;BTW, etymologically, the word &ldquo;patient&rdquo; comes from the Latin &ldquo;pati,&rdquo; which means&nbsp;&ldquo;sufferer.). <br /><br />Now, we\'re deep in tangled weeds and neglect on health care, medical care, big pharama. We\'re lost. Nothing is clear. The economics are bizarre if not crazed and are being exploited for profits. We only think of cost. Issues of caring, empathy, compassion - the values nurses and doctors are trained to support - get blindsided by hospital administrative rules that prioritize costs. Caring is not part of our discussion for change. We\'re being led by the wrong narrative. We must value caring as much as cost. <br /><br />I suspect that if significant research were carried out, industry leaders would love to get rid of paying for health care insurance.If nothing else, it\'s an expensive drag on profits left over from a WWII improvisation. Relieve business of the burden. If industry can find the means to insure healthy workers, why can\'t our government? Profits? Control? Old ways of thinking?'),
(29, '2018-11-22', 'On Marty\'s 83d Birthday', '', 'A few minutes ago we brought our entire family together on Facetime in images (almost everyone, Liam had tech problems so we could only hear him) and words and good crack, as the Irish would say. &rsquo;Twas a 21st Century Engineering Miracle. <br /><br />I know, Engineers don&rsquo;t do miracles, but this hour and a half, four-way conversation in color didn&rsquo;t cost us a penny and that is a miracle. I once called home from Ireland. It was about 1980 and I was charged $12.00 a minute. Now? Zero. Nothing. Have a good time, it\'s free. <br /><br />The Kaufman&rsquo;s, Zandra and Michael were on from Santa Cruz, CA, looking good at about 10AM their time and the Kroes family was on from Euroland at about 7pm their time including Liam from Amsterdam and the rest, Koos, Sean, and Amelia from Millingen a/d Rijn. All the resonances were positive! And here we were in South Carolina around noon happily sharing it all with everybody. <br /><br />Turkey and stuffing were not necessary to celebrate this big communal, relationships day, Thanksgiving. We did put a special shine on the day &lsquo;cause it is also Marty&rsquo;s 83d. After spinning around the Sun 83 times, she got home from her work at Hospice just in time to hear the cheers and birthday wishes from our family across the planet. Now, she is preparing her most desirable feast: 1/2 pound lobster tails. Two of them. The turkey lived to see another day, and I&rsquo;m very well taken care of.'),
(27, '2018-11-12', 'On the nature of the human spirit', '', 'I&rsquo;ve come to know my place in the universe. From the day I rejected the doctrines of childhood at age 18, &rsquo;til I experienced the unimpeachable answer to that question, I spent decades searching. <br /><br />Note, that I say &ldquo;experienced.&rdquo; My story is not about learning a belief system taught by others. The experience that changed me happened while reading at my desk. In a moment, the search ended, but those years of searching were essential because the searching prepared me to fully understand the shocking power and wonder of what I&rsquo;d just read. <br /><br />I&rsquo;m not sure it would have impacted me that way, had I not been a fan of science, searched the world&rsquo;s religions, studied Zen for a short while in a monastery, dropped acid, and looked always, even in mirrors, for the answer to &ldquo;who am I?&rdquo; <br /><br />Then I read, what is today a simple, universally accepted fact, stars create matter. Einstein&rsquo;s equation: E=MC squared.&nbsp; Suddenly, everything came together into an unforeseen, all embracing One-ness.&nbsp; That was about 45 years ago. The impact of the experience has never weakened or faltered. <br /><br />What did I learn? That my matter, atoms and molecules, were created in a star that exploded, casting everything it made into space.&nbsp; Maybe many stars, many eons ago, took part in that cosmic seeding. It means I was out there once in the form of my little bits. So were we all.&nbsp; I find that terribly exciting.&nbsp; To know it means that we are a little bit of the universe aware of itself. <br /><br />Eventually, gravity whirled all the little bits into a vast togetherness that formed a cosmic cloud, which produced our Sun and its planets. Then Earth produced life out of its soil and water and air. I am one of those living critters and&nbsp; we&rsquo;ve all emerged from Earth&rsquo;s soil. <br /><br />And that tells me the human spirit comes from the soil, the rocks, the air, the water.&nbsp; We emerged from all that, all of us.&nbsp; The planet is where I came from.&nbsp; And because I&rsquo;m related to all the other life on Earth, I have a responsibility to care for it.&nbsp; That&rsquo;s my purpose. <br /><br />I know the other arguments and beliefs about our source. In fact, there are many and they all have many believers.I&rsquo;ve no argument with any of those other narratives. If they resolve a searcher&rsquo;s needs, they have value. <br /><br />I must say, though, that as a child of nature, I do not support the idea of the &ldquo;supernatural.&rdquo; Not one bit of testable evidence for the existence of a supernatural has ever been offered in all of human history. No testable evidence. Never. <br /><br />My search has ended. I am content and willing to own all that I am, whether mistakes or faults, as well as my values, the most of important of which is the Golden Rule. <br /><br />By the way, I see a validation for my cosmic experience in the ancient wisdom of our language. Words like human, humane, humus, humor, humanity, humble, or humanist suggest to me that we&rsquo;ve known all along who we are.'),
(28, '2018-11-17', 'On careerism and relationships', '', 'I\'ve just been reading an interesting conversation at On Being with the eminent journalist Anand Giridharadas that focused on the dangers of too much power in the hands of the hyper wealthy. The conversation brought to the surface an idea I\'ve been toying with for a long time, but have not yet taken the time to think through, and that is the widely accepted, even dominant cultural idea, that it should be our purpose to prepare for, engage in, and climb to the top of a career. <br /><br />The subtext is that we value maximum competition over collaboration because the latter is a communal value and competition the better value because it helps one - the struggling individual - to climb the ladder of career. We need to examine the primacy of careerism as a cultural value. It isn\'t that developing a career is bad, but we need to value the cultivation of our relationships as much as our careers. <br /><br />In other words, perhaps we ought come to a point wherein we value a career primarily because said career will help our relationships to flourish. Nurturing relationship leads to a richer human experience that includes not only our relationships with other people but with the planet and all of its children. <br /><br />The drive behind careerism leads to the primacy of money and fame. That, in my view, is pretty thin soup compared to the possibilities of our relationships with each othe. Moderate success in a career can encourage relationships and bring them to fruition.'),
(31, '2018-11-25', 'The diminishing dominance of technology', '', 'I find myself becoming - little by little - alienated by the ever more complicated demands of our new technology. As I find that happening in me, I wonder more and more if there will be a reaction against, a turning away from the - let\'s call them \"popular\" - technologies that have done so much, captivated so many, and changed the way we live. <br /><br />Other kinds of technologies have captivated societies before, including painting and sculpture in the Renaissance. Music in the 18th and 19th centuries were techs that dominated. Then people turned from them to other new and effective tools beginning with steam power. <br /><br />What will our children turn to that fascinates them when they lose their jobs to robots? Humans have always been makers. As makers we usually begin by playing with, exploring with our tools.&nbsp;<br /><br />I can imagine a marvelous out come of our devotion to tech; a world transformed into makers, artists creating stunning new expressions of culture adapting the new tools to focus on the dominance of hand made things again?'),
(30, '2018-11-23', 'Hillary turns Right', '', 'THE GUARDIAN reports Hillary&rsquo;s suggestion to Euro leaders about migrants/refugees from the Mideast and Africa. She says, &ldquo;I think Europe needs to get a handle on migration because that is what lit the flame,&rdquo; she said. &hellip; &ldquo;we are not going to be able to continue provide refuge and support [for] the migration issue [It] will continue to roil the body politic.&rdquo; <br /><br />From my pov, it is the way migrants are used by extremist politicians to inflame the populace that is the issue. <br /><br />I&rsquo;ve always wanted Hillary to succeed, but I&rsquo;ve also had to watch the Whiz Kid from Wellesley fall into sink-holes of her own making. viz. personal email as Sec&rsquo;y of State. <br /><br />Here she helps the authoritarian Right Wingers in Europe who ginned up the issue using fear-of-the-other, instead of finding ways to practice compassion. Now, she&rsquo;s using a Trump tactic. I suspect that if you&rsquo;re burdened by untrammeled ambition, the push to win never weakens and easily serves to block moral insight. Voters sense it.'),
(33, '2018-12-06', 'Who are we?  Really?', '', 'Have you noticed the frequent talk in the media about &ldquo;identity politics?&rdquo; There&rsquo;s a piece in today&rsquo;s NYTimes that illustrates what I&rsquo;m talking about. A reader writes that \"he cannot sell his daughter on celebrating Hanukkah the way he did as a child with jelly donuts and eight nights of presents.&rdquo;The presents are a way for Jewish kids to get holiday presents like Christians. <br /><br />So his daughter&rsquo;s &ldquo;identity&rdquo; as a Jew is changing? If so, her father&rsquo;s changed too because &ldquo;more rigidly observant Jews will scold [him] because the &ldquo;real&rdquo; Hanukkah has no presents to give. In other words, if you don&rsquo;t observe correctly it &ldquo;is a betrayal&rdquo; of the tradition and therefore of your &ldquo;identity.&rdquo; <br /><br />We&rsquo;ve been watching the same conflict for a couple of decades between those who say &ldquo;Happy Holidays&rdquo; and &ldquo;Merry Christmas.&rdquo; The implication being that if you don&rsquo;t say it right, you betray the Christian tradition. People get into serious fights about these tribal requirements. <br /><br />In fact, we are simply watching old cultural ways of establishing membership in the tribe (identity) collapse and give way to new clues to another identity. In these cases the new ID is neither Jewish nor Christian. It is American. And this has been going on for a long time in various tribal and religious traditions. <br /><br />For many, especially elders, there has been too much change. They need it to stop. They cheer to make America the way it was before the changes. And at the root of all the conflict is that people raised to the tribal traditions (including the new ones) do not know who they are if they think our ID is defined by tribal ways. <br /><br />We all have a much bigger Identity than our little tribal/social ID. We all have a gender, a name, and one overall identity: we are simply humans. <br /><br />THAT is who we are. We can accept and play with and enjoy those tribal tropes we learned from childhood, but we have to understand that we are more than that. When we don&rsquo;t accept our common humanity as our identity, we&rsquo;re headed for trouble.'),
(34, '2018-12-08', 'On the loss of the sacred in human life', '', 'When I was a kid, the common mantra we all heard constantly repeated was &ldquo;Learn to respect the sacredness of human life.&rdquo; It didn&rsquo;t matter your religion or politics or whether you were working class or wealthy, educated or not. Human life was deemed sacred and we were all inculcated with that value. It took a thug like Dillinger to make headlines, and lynchings happened. We had the worst wars in history. But we believed life was sacred. Today? Not as much. <br /><br />Ordinary people - not thugs or bigots -are savaging ordinary people, taking lives with cars, trucks, knives, any other handy weapon. It&rsquo;s <strong>not just guns</strong>, but it is only guns we debate. We seem to ignore a lost sacredness, and think the tool is responsible for our deeds. <br /><br />But we know we are now threatened by more than one tool. The preciousness of life has been discounted. And any tool will do.&nbsp;<br /><br />Ordinary people probably expect attacks from other ordinary people who are not thought to be a threat. A child? Yes. Maybe, even likely. Attacks happen anywhere, anytime. At a public meeting, in Temples, Churches, schools, restaurants, sporting events, clubs, town halls. On the street.<br /><br />Mostly the attackers are our own people, not foreigners. Yes, of course, those we call &ldquo;terrorists&rdquo; are part of this general descent into a hell of alienation and disrespect. But aren&rsquo;t all attackers terrorists? <br /><br />NRA members demand weapons because they fear attacks. NRA opponents fear attacks by ordinary people with weapons. We all fear the same thing, that our lives are no longer regarded as sacred, revered. <br /><br />Compassion? Empathy? The Golden Rule? We&rsquo;ve discounted those values. Has the IRA ever mentioned compassion? Of course not. Compassion is an emblem of weakness. Right? Pretty much. We only debate the economic costs of attacks. Values don\'t count for much. <br /><br />We also encourage killings by giving so much attention to killers. One idea: <strong>Never again mention an attacker&rsquo;s name in the media, no more notoriety for &nbsp;killers.</strong> <br /><br />As for shootings, The Guardian reports today that &ldquo;2018 is worst year on record for gun violence in schools. Research by the US Naval Postgraduate School (NPS) shows 94 incidents in 2018, a near 60% increase on the previous high, 59, set in 2006.&rdquo; <strong>But people are also using bombs and anything that can kill.</strong> We should include all weapons in our count. And not just mass killings. How about family killings? Stabbings in the subways. Whatever. <br /><br />So, what is the dominant value we actually place on human life in our society today? Is it indifference to the lives of others because we feel alone, disconnected? The dominant value is certainly not that all human lives are sacred. Thus, when I go to a meeting or a restaurant or park on the lot at the supermarket, I wonder, &ldquo;It could happen now. Will it?&rdquo; I don\'t think I\'m the only one who expects attacks to happen. &nbsp;Any time. &nbsp;Any place.<br /><br />Any ideas?<br />2018-12-09'),
(35, '2018-12-20', 'Another year ends.', '', 'Hey there, Friends and Lovers, we are in the time of Saturnalia. From December 23 to 25th, depending on your historian, the Romans raised hell. Before them our ancestors celebrated the winter equinox, the return of the light, for forty millennia. And now? Comes Merry Christmas. <br /><br />It&rsquo;ll be a good day. Believe. When I was seven or six or eight, all the family came together on Christmas Eve and celebrated being together. It wasn&rsquo;t so much the Lord&rsquo;s time as family fun time. <br />We gave each other knockers, &ldquo;Yeah, Uncle Gene, a roll of pennies. Put &lsquo;em in your shoes and you won&rsquo;t have the flat feet that kept you out of the army.&rdquo; <br /><br />We had a hell of a good time together. We played with the toys and competed for laughs. The uncles were fun. For a change. Mother and Daddy were actually there on the spot. She had her kitchen duties done, which always included a twenty pounder ready for the oven. He had closed up his drive-in pre-Big-Mac burger shop and stayed home - at last! - for one night. We played, we teased. It was marvelous, magical. Christmas Eve gave us all a reason for life and living. And it had to do with us, only us. We were the focus and we contemplated no supernatural beings. <br /><br />We were there as our ancestors had been in their caves for 40 thousand years celebrating the Return of the Light. We didn&rsquo;t know that&rsquo;s what we were doing, we played because it was the night for people to play. <br /><br />When I got to be 12 all that went away with the spirit of Santa Claus. I had long known he was fake news. Something else went missing tho, my innocence. I had begun to develop an ego. I could be easily hurt. Play had become unfunny. I had lost my toddler\'s importance. <br /><br />Uncles showed me I had lessons to learn, told me I needed to listen to my elders. The priests and nuns at church and school had become enforcers of obedience. Daddy told me I could develop duck-like webbing between my fingers or even go to an insane asylum if I continued &hellip; that &hellip; you know. I&rsquo;m still reluctant to use bad words. <br /><br />Now it&rsquo;s 80 years later. We have a growing custom to look back over the year and share the best with friends. Did we do it right? I dunno, but I can tell you that being alive has resulted in a splended spin around the Sun. <br /><br />We&rsquo;re still living a week better than pay-check to pay-check. We haven&rsquo;t taken out the boat for months. It&rsquo;d be better to use it. We have gardens that are barely flourishing. We call them woodland forests, another word for neglecting to chop out saplings and seedlings. <br /><br />The House is in pretty good shape because of a crew of Mexican guys who have been doing the hard labor for the last 17 years. Good people. One problem though, their boss went up onto our roof the other day to blow off the leaves? It&rsquo;s a metal roof. Slippy. And yes. He fell off. <br /><br />Grim. The word is that he broke a wrist and needs dental work. Lots of concerns here about that. We love the guy, but what happens next? Don&rsquo;t know. We&rsquo;ll keep you up to date. <br /><br />Went out to Santa Cruz to spend a couple weeks with both Amelia and Alexandra and their husbands, Koos (auf Nederlands) and Michael, Alexandra&rsquo;s husband. Marvelous. <br /><br />It was great to be together. Their gardens are so beautiful, we took pride in them. Michael has a Tesla and arranged for us to drive a new one. Zero to 60 in one second! Well, it felt like that. He arranged for us to experience a big 8 passenger model. When it introduces itself, that four wheeled robot defines fantastic. <br /><br />See the eight of us standing in the drive way in front of the garage. Michael presses a button, the doors go up, the Tesla emerges without a driver, and decides when to stop. We&rsquo;re all standing around California dreaming. The big Tesla [kinda looks around], decides it\'s time to play music. Then it dances. It&rsquo;s middle doors rise up and down to the rhythm, rear mirrors move back and forth. Front doors open and close, rear door does its part. Did it shimmy? Not sure. But it goes through a five minute welcoming gig that earned cheers. Yes. We stood there applauding a four wheeled robot. <br /><br />That brings me up to date for the first six months. In my next chapter, we&rsquo;ll explore my nine month adventure as a political candidate running for Oconee SC County Council as a Democrat. More later. <br />Love all y&rsquo;all, B'),
(36, '2018-12-23', 'On intelligence testing', '', 'Aeon reports that the highest scorers in intelligence/aptitude tests can be predicted to do well in society. A lively debate in the social/psychological communities suggests that tests of these kinds are biased socially as in, would a test designed in Tokyo work in Rotterdam? <br /><br />Or, to put it differently, &ldquo;Just prove you&rsquo;re smart and follow tribal rules, you&rsquo;ll be fine.\" But as those old tribal ways get more and more undermined, and there&rsquo;s not much of the old ethos left here, we see many more impetuous decisions being made. It feels scary. It&rsquo;s like the tests didn&rsquo;t work and we&rsquo;ve put fools in charge. <br /><br />The article brings back how, as a kid, I recoiled whenever they put one of these tests in front of me. I don&rsquo;t know why, but I disrespected them. Maybe I didn&rsquo;t want myself revealed. Anyway, I messed with one in the army, got called in and threatened with a courts martial.<br /><br />From a dramatic pov, it was all farce. However, also from that pov, I&rsquo;ll argue that unpredicted, well considered and not impetuous, behavior makes for interesting characters, not numbers, but we like data. <br /><br />Which reminds me of the question about the number of angels on the head of a pin. Used to be angels, now it&rsquo;s data.'),
(37, '2018-12-28', 'Overwhelming Change and its consequences', '', 'There&rsquo;ve been too many changes, and it&rsquo;s not just tech. The never-before-in-human-history cultural changes together with the tech changes of the last generation have overwhelmed many of us in the older generations. I&rsquo;m 87 today. I think MAGA will lose its legs when our generation - 70 and more - dies off. <br />Youth (under 70) must be part of the calculation for Democracy, its future, and the impact of tech. I feel a reaction in me against tech. Tech makes life both easier and more challenging, especially as it becomes more complex. I sometimes spend as much time talking to Mumbai about tech support as I do working. That is a waste, and sometimes emotionally exhausting because algorithms were not created with elders in mind. <br /><br />From my perspective today&rsquo;s tech feels like my uncle&rsquo;s Model T. He spent more time working with the damn thing to keep it running, than he did driving it. He had to crank it to get it started. That&rsquo;s the way tech is for me. &hellip;especially passwords, which are like getting out and cranking the Model T. Tech needs a simple starter button. <br /><br />BUT, and here is the essential point, it&rsquo;s not just tech. Every aspect of the culture has been challenged since WWII and those challenges and changes will not go away just because the Trumpist crowd has been given a chance to turn things back to 1951 (the year, by the way) we were losing thousands of men in our never ending Korean Police Action War. <br /><br />Blacks and women won&rsquo;t go back to MAGA and from my pov, tribalism, which is our culture&rsquo;s main theme these days, will wither. And that won&rsquo;t be good for American football. <br /><br />So, I recommend we contemplate all the changes in sexual attitudes, religious attitudes, table manners, non-existent service at service stations, militarized local cops, our use of trains, our submission to airline policies, and an endless list that could fill this page. We, in my generation, think of those changes a lot, and whether we like &lsquo;em or not, we -I- are beginning to react negatively to the never ending rush of change! <br /><br />At the same time, I can foresee a more interesting future arising from AI when the arts and handicrafts will rise again. Think about it. The most significant tech in the 17th and 18th centuries focused on developments in the arts: music, its software, and its instruments for one.'),
(38, '2019-01-23', 'Composting Bodies? Not much.', '', 'Is composting bodies a good idea for this culture? In parts of India/Persia the dead have long been put out on a platform on a mountain top and left for birds to consume. &nbsp;I wrote a play in which the hero demands -to the consternation of everybody else - that his body be put out for animals to consume. &nbsp;<br /><br />Traveling in Italy and Turkey we&rsquo;ve seen many empty old sarcophagi, big 3x8ft, cut-stone boxes wherein bodies were placed to decompose: sar (flesh) cophagi (eat). &nbsp;Eat the flesh.&nbsp; That seems to explain what happened to the flesh that had been on the bones that ended in catacombs. <br /><br />Bodies were decomposed, &nbsp;bones took up less space underground than we we use with coffin-sarcophogi we use buried with the body. <br /><br />Catacomb workers artfully arranged all the bones together.&nbsp;I like the aesthetic sensibility you can see in these catacomb pictures. (google: pictures catacomb bones.) Tender care plus a wish to create attractive patterns with bones are evident. They didn\'t just dump bones in the catacomb. &nbsp;Early modern cave art. <br /><br />Read about places like Hart Island, the island of the dead, in New York City. They\'re now digging up over a million skeletons of people who died without friends or families and were buried there in a pauper\'s grave. It sounds like the operators didn\'t realize they were using the ground itself as a gigantic sarcophagus. &nbsp;Now they have the bones to deal with. Some have recommended those bones should be cremated in power plants to create electricity, which could be seen as a kind of resurrection, a coming of the light. A special day could be set aside for the burning of the bones. A happy holiday like the Mexican Day of the Dead. It\'s an idea that could spread.<br /><br />&nbsp;The nuns in my school would not have liked that idead, though. &nbsp;They taught us that cremation disobeyed God\'s Law. God planned to raise all bodies from the dead and judge at the Final Judgment whether they would spend eternity in heaven or hell. I didn&rsquo;t think about it when I was a kid, but now I can see the cremations would have been a good way for felons to escape both the Final Judgment and the eternal fires of hell. &nbsp;Dust to dust.<br /><br />Woody Allen explored resurrection in Sleeper. &nbsp; <br /><br />Pioneers moving west are said to have covered their dead along the way with a pile of rocks &ldquo;so critters won&rsquo;t get at them&rdquo; - sounds like a kind of &ldquo;loose stone\" sarcophagus.&nbsp; Today, anthropologists at the University of &nbsp;Tennessee, Knoxville (?) have a study going on in an uninhabited area. It&rsquo;s called the &ldquo;Body Farm.&rdquo; Bodies are put out around the Farm on the ground in various ways and the process of decomposition gets studied scientifically, step by step. It&rsquo;s a way for anthropologists to study other cultures without having to go there. &nbsp; &nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_farm\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Body_farm </a><br /><br />The New York Times article (link below) includes a picture of a machine at the University of Washington that is used to speed up decomposition. It is like a sarcophagus American style; monetize the process for 5000 bucks a body. It seems to include lawn grass as an essential ingredient in decomposition. <br /><br />Green. Yes. Perhaps future green families could install a box on the roof when they put in solar. I can imagine a nice ritual associated with sending the dead to heaven or to the cosmos - your choice - leaving behind only bones to be ground up and scattered on the flower garden. Feed the birds, feed the flowers. The box could be left open for birds or closed for bugs. Could cause neighborhood problems, tho. <br /><br />Then, of course there&rsquo;s Green Burial,at Memorial Ecosystems, the process that Kimberley and Billy Campbell in Westminster, SC, began in the USA about 20 years ago. Get a forest and a licence, survey, then dig hole, put in a body, join the natural processes of decomposition,&nbsp;and protect nature by slowing development of forests. &nbsp;That objective is a good Green objective and would help protect natural lands that are now at risk of development. &nbsp;Billy and Kimberley would like to see a million acres protected.<br /><br />( Read the NYTimes article that stimulated these ideas composting here: https://www.nytimes.com/2019/01/26/us/death-human-compost.html?action=click&amp;module=News&amp;pgtype=Homepage');
