(39, '2019-02-04', 'Managing Face Pain', '', 'I have had to deal with trigeminal neuralgia for seventeen years. It is a savage, intolerable pain not touched by opioids. At first, my excellent doc tried Tegretol with ever diminishing results. We switched to a lab-made THC that is normally used for cancer patients. <br /><br />Over night I went from 500mgs Tegretol with possible side effects that could affect my liver, to 2.5mgs of THC 24/7, which masks the pain 99.99%. It is legal, prescribed, and insurance pays. There are no side effects other than a trivial, rarely experienced, sense of being stoned, which does not affect my work, and quickly clears up. I carry a copy of the script with my driver\'s licence. Just in case. <br /><br />Some docs are timid, and rigidly follow established protocols. The truth is that when they try to prohibit, they do not serve suffering people with empathy, on the face of it a bad idea.'),
(40, '2019-02-10', 'Adapting At the ER', '', 'At age 83, my Marty, aka Margaret, works as a Hospice volunteer, goes twice a week, works with staff and patients and friends and relatives who come to visit. They love her, and - of course - she dismisses praise, calls herself a servant, does lots of little jobs for patients and staff, and even drops an occasional suggestion on bewildered visitors like, \"Just be present, have a seat, you\'ll know what to say or do.\"<br /><br />She comes home with funny stories about interactions she&rsquo;s had; mostly they\'re stories about patients and staff members and the good humor and relationships among them. The Hospice is a good place for her to work. <br /><br />I&rsquo;m not sure I&rsquo;d manage as well in a hospital, tho. She\'d probably be more adept than I. I need an attitude adjustment because of what happened after I found myself wheeled into an emergency room one night recently. My spine had stopped holding me erect, and dropped me on the floor in exquisite pain at a hotel check-in desk. <br /><br />Unable to walk, I arrived at the ER in an ambulance, and waited there, twisted and unable to move in an ER bed for seven hours, reassured two or three times that &ldquo;there are 14 really sick people ahead of you,\" until a doc came and gave me a shot at 3AM. I walked out 15 minutes later with Marty and friend, Steve, both of whom had also waited without anyone giving them any attention. I left in an ungood mood. <br /><br />Their excuse? &ldquo;We must follow protocols, Sir.&rdquo; But I think empathy should rule, however, we live with what we get, so, I&rsquo;ll work on attitude adjustment.'),
(41, '2019-02-10', 'A Most Powerful Speech', '', 'Take a look at my nomination for the most powerful, most courageous, and smartest speech in the last two years. Before you watch, imagine who might have given this extraordinary speech. <br /><br />Lest we forget: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=u46HzTGVQhg'),
(42, '2019-02-10', ' An Abnormal Relationship', '', 'It gradually became clear to me that I was developing an abnormal relationship with my stomach. &nbsp;I wanted flat. I knew it&rsquo;d be sexier to look rippt. &nbsp;Is that the right word? Either way, I couldn&rsquo;t get it. &nbsp;The damn thing insisted on round the bigger the round the better. I figured that the problem has to do with feeding the damn thing. At least that&rsquo;s the received wisdom, but no. Not feeding it doesn&rsquo;t work.&nbsp; <br /><br />It doesn&rsquo;t work if you take it to the gym and work like a beast trying to make it flat. That won&rsquo;t do it either. &nbsp;I&rsquo;ve considered radical methods like surgery, but then you have to trust docs. You have to find one without a round one. They&rsquo;re hard to find. &nbsp;I thought maybe a fem doc would be a good surgeon to consult, so I did that. And you know what? She touched me, and I didn&rsquo;t give her permission. So I felt a little abused. You know? Boy or girl, it doesn&rsquo;t matter. &nbsp;Abuse is abuse. You have to say yes before you get touched. So. I walked out, didn&rsquo;t pay. Nothing. &nbsp; <br /><br />Now a collection agency is hammering on the door, phoning me all the time, threatening to cut my credit score. &nbsp;About that I couldn&rsquo;t give a poop. \"Go ahead and cut it, Sweetie,\" I said. &nbsp;It was a guy and he didn&rsquo;t like me calling him sweetie, said he&rsquo;d report me for abuse and that&rsquo;s where I am now with my abnormal stomach. &nbsp;I have no other relationships.&rdquo;'),
(43, '2019-02-11', 'Truck Stop Shirley, a celebration of diversity and pride', '', 'The other day a live performance celebrating Black History Month came to OLLI at Clemson University. OLLI is Clemson&rsquo;s successful long life learning program with some 1500 members. A major theme associated with the program is the promotion of diversity, and this show, Truck Stop Shirley, successfully contributed to that ideal. The room was more than full, when there were no more seats available, people stood, even outside the doors. There were probably 150 there, and they were almost all white. <br /><br />On stage there were 8 performers, black men and women, actors, poets, singers, preachers, &amp; an older blind woman, Blind Betty, who played the lead, and one white, me, the MC. From my perspective it was a marvelous event. As a long time director, I watched the audience throughout and especially at the curtain call. They showed their approval with energetic laughter and applause. At the end the chairs were still filled. <br /><br />The focus of the show is a woman from this part of South Carolina who, born in 1938, was raised in a share cropper home as one of ten children who picked cotton for the white farmer. When the cotton market failed, the owner sold out to a truck stop operator where Shirley, the eldest of the cotton picker&rsquo;s ten children, went from picking to learning to drive a bulldozer for the contractor, to washing dishes when the truck stop opened, and gradually becoming waitress, short order cook, and finally boss of the operation which became known to truckers as Truck Stop Shirley. <br /><br />The primary theme of Rev. Dr. Romando James&rsquo; production is Pride. It is a stirring lesson in how Miss Shirley applied herself, worked hard, dealt with whites, and succeeded. And Dr James succeeded with that audience of white faces, whose applause and non-verbal&rsquo;s testified to this MC that they loved the show.'),
(44, '2019-02-10', 'Inculcating racism - an American phenomenon', '', '<p>My wife, Margaret, asked me to post something about the racial conditioning I experienced as a child. I&rsquo;m glad she did.&nbsp;<br /><br />I&rsquo;m 87. I hope my experiences with racism were the exception when I grew up in the nineteen thirties and forties as a white kid in SE Pennsylvania. When I was five, my black friend, also five, kissed me. My uncle saw him do it and told me I&rsquo;d get the kissing disease that made people black. He may have thought himself witty. He wasn&rsquo;t, his words made a deep emotional impression on my unconscious mind. I think those deep and mostly unconscious ideas still impact and influence people of my generation in the USA. <br /><br />It has been said that the Pennsylvania RR conductors who went through the train as it went south across the Mason-Dixon Line, called out, &ldquo;All niggers to the crow car.&rdquo; &nbsp;If so, surely, he thought his instructions to do so were ok. They were not.&nbsp;It is a sad irony that in our Pennsylvania town, blacks literally lived only on the other side of tracks owned by the PRR.&nbsp;<br /><br />I learned from relatives and friends, from the culture I lived in, from radio shows like <em>Amos and Andy </em>to think of African blacks as a race of lesser human beings, good people, but inferior. I&rsquo;m sure we Euro whites passed around personal anecdotes and stories that reinforced that evil idea.&nbsp;<br /><br />My point is this, those are stories with a long life-time in the human soul. It&rsquo;s malware we have to delete. &nbsp;We deal with racism by acknowledging it\'s in us and reminding ourselves it is wrong. I&rsquo;m still working out decades of that old Pennsylvania racism, and I&rsquo;m not finished.</p>'),
(45, '2019-02-18', 'Of LORENA, a film about cultural ugliness', '', 'Watched LORENA last night. I wish I had not put that story, as told in this skilfully made documentary, into my mind. The underlying themes are cultural ugliness, depravity, cruelty and an endless need in the culture to dominate, control, and punish women. <br /><br />It&rsquo;s Lorena&rsquo;s story. John Wayne Bobbit (so much irony in his name) comes off in person as vulgar and stupid, a soul sick, conventionally handsome Marine. Perhaps more disturbing is that so many others in the piece laughed both at him and with him. <br /><br />This culture has a rot in its core, breeding repulsiveness in damn near every character in the film. We need more elements in our culture that breed and encourage compassion. Instead we discount it. The film hardly recognizes its existence.'),
(46, '2019-02-20', 'Should we blame students if the teacher is boring?', '', '<p>A BBC article today reports that teachers are having difficulty teaching because kids are paying attention to iPhones and other devices instead of their good teachers. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;ve been a teacher all my life.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>We in the teaching profession say our first obligation on the job is to motivate students and<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>hold their attention.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>We teachers have always been challenged by students (of every age) who get interested in things other than what we want them to hear.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>When I was a kid in Catholic school, I was a daydreamer who just wasn&rsquo;t necessarily interested in what the nuns had to say. &lsquo;Course, that could earn me a crack on the knuckles with an oak ruler. Not a great motivator. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Later on, the docs and big pharma got interested. They claimed the daydreamers were diseased and needed medication to deal with their attention deficits. They also gave it a meaningless abstract name that gave away their game: ADHD.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Now it&rsquo;s technology that gets attention and causes disorder.</p>\r\n<p>C&rsquo;mon, stop blaming kids for not listening to boring stuff. Demand that teachers motivate. Skillful professional teachers, imaginative teachers, creative teachers, good teachers will recognize that it is THEIR job to get and hold student attention tech or no tech.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Teachers are like actors, lawyers, and other attention getters.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>They can learn how to engage and hold in ways that students will accept even enjoy.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; <br /><br /></span>And please, Teach, don&rsquo;t blame the subject matter you are paid to teach. Consider yourself part performer like actors or lawyers who only get paid if the audience attends to them.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>That same requirement for a paycheck ought be a basic qualification for teachers. Engage and hold the attention of those kids who own iPhones or you might be blamed for not attending to their need to learn. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>'),
(47, '2019-02-28', 'The Purpose of Life - from a 21st Century Perspective', '', '<p>Across the world, humanity has always had three basic questions: Who are we? &nbsp;Where&rsquo;d we come from? And what is our purpose? A common answer to #3 among educated people today, those who have given up religion, is that there&rsquo;s no point to our existence. Nihilism reigns. The universe is indifferent. Religionists will argue differently. I&rsquo;m not a religionist, but I see a purpose, one humanity must come to recognize, accept, and articulate for our own survival.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<br />Our purpose derives from the fact that every atom in our bodies was cooked into being in stars. Who are we? We&rsquo;re starstuff. We came from an exploded star that had cooked into being all the atoms in our bodies. That cosmic material became humans, ants, oaks, and every other living thing. We came out of Earth&rsquo;s rocks. And we know that. We&rsquo;ve also learned that the universe becomes aware of itself in us.&nbsp;<br /><br />Knowing these facts means we have responsibility to ourselves and the rest of life. We must take care of our cousins and our earth. That is the great and transcendent task that takes us beyond the narrow grasp of old tribalism. That we don&rsquo;t realize it, suggests we are still a bit adolescent. To grow up, we need to accept our responsibilities and debate about how best to carry them out. &nbsp;'),
(54, '2019-05-19', 'Clues to the collapse of Patriarchal thinking', '', 'The movement of voters toward people like Orban, Salvini, and Le Pen in Europe remind me of the movement of dissatisfied people toward Fascism in Germany, Italy, and Spain in the 1920s. And I&rsquo;m confident those three leaders and Trump could organize Black Shirt semi-military organizations now, but they don&rsquo;t seem to dare. <br /><br />I sense they are supported by people whose tribal origins are being threatened. Immigrant issues looms large over there and here. There&rsquo;s also a strong distaste for the most wealthy and powerful. That&rsquo;s the secular aspect. <br /><br />There is also a swift movement away from traditional churches going on in Europe and the USA. In the current Atlantic magazine, June 2019, a former priest advocates what is essentially a return to the customs of early Christianity when where there was no episcopacy. That means no Vatican. <br /><br />This conflict is manifest in the extraordinary conflict going public between the two popes.<br /><br /><a href=\"https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/06/to-save-the-church-dismantle-the-priesthood/588073/\"> https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2019/06/to-save-the-church-dismantle-the-priesthood/588073/ </a><br /><br />It all gets more interesting if one extricates oneself from politics, and steps back from partisan front lines, and the political agitation. From that perspective, one can see clues that suggest we are in the midst of a change bigger than the gargantuan changes we&rsquo;ve lived through in the last 75 years. <br /><br />Get away from partisanship and it is possible to see the whole Patriarchal tradition and all of its components under threat by a new leadership of men and women who reject all the old orthodoxies of Patriarchal culture, religious and secular. <br /><br />Watch one example, AOC on the Green revolution at https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iZyiZ2dXtVc&amp;t=494s. You may dismiss her and discount her, but millions are cheering. <br /><br />And examine the impressive personal quality of Pete Buttigieg on <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2DMVu6CLZ4.\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=x2DMVu6CLZ4. </a><br /><br />AOC, Buttigieg, and people like them are talking humanist policies like health care and climate change policies first. The misogynistic old guys who created what we have now are all on their way out. I would love to get a Ticket to Ride to 2119 and see what happens.'),
(48, '2019-04-30', 'On Play, do we value free play?', '', '<p>Not much. Do we understand it? Maybe not, yet free play brings us together. If relationships were based on free play it would fill our lives. The problem is that free play is too often thought of as childishly trivial. We tend to think of the word play to mean playing competitive games like golf, football, or poker. &nbsp;<br /><br />Free play is different. It\'s the opposite of aggressive games that devolved through competition, has no mistakes and only one rule. <br /><br />And I\'m not talking about acting like a childish fool. Free play produces the opposite of losers and fools.&nbsp;<br /><br />A good conversation employs free play. Free play always works, is fun, and it heals. Jazz artists and improv actors play freely, thinking, &ldquo;OK, I got your gift of music, of words, and I&rsquo;ll take it further.&rdquo; <br /><br />I am suggesting we employ one simple rule. We call it the rule of improvisation, accept what you get from the other person or situation, and immediately take the risk that your response will take what is happening in the relationship to the next step without censoring yourself. You will find there are no mistakes, only opportunities. The result is creative and fun.<br /><br />Understand this, when I say &ldquo;accept what you get,&rdquo; I am not saying you should agree. To accept is not to agree. It is to say, &ldquo;Yes, and&hellip;&rdquo; When you accept whatever you get with &ldquo;Yes, and &hellip;&rdquo; you will be respected, maybe thought witty, usually perceived as humble, and both of you will come away happier.&nbsp;<br /><br />Imagine you are sitting on the deck with friends. Conversation has become droopy. Imagine a basketball in your hands. Shape it. Feel it. Say nothing. &ldquo;Bounce&rdquo; it up and down on the floor. Catch the eye of a friend. Toss the ball. I bet they&rsquo;ll toss it back. The chances are the other friends will want to play ball too. And smiles will automatically form on lips all around you.</p>\r\n<p>So, next time someone says something you agree or disagree with, suppress any impulse to say, &ldquo;no.&rdquo; Instead, say &ldquo;yes,&rdquo; and -if you want to be friends - instantly say or do what comes next without disagreeing. If we could all do this, difficult relationships would become positive overnight.&nbsp;<br /><br />Here comes the ball.</p>'),
(49, '2019-03-21', 'The Decline of White Power', '', '<p>The decline began with the collapse of white colonialism in the &lsquo;40s,<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>just after &ldquo;The Great Generation won\" WWII.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;During&nbsp;</span>those post war years colonies all over the world started to throw off White Power.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;White Power</span>&nbsp;won the war, but lost the history of our time. Brexiteers got angry. So, they voted to Remove England from being under the control of Europe. They got a taste of their own medicine and didn\'t like it.</p>\r\n<p>The White Power Era began in the 16th century. Whites from Euroland eventually dominated the Philippines and Indonesia, the Chinese, South East Asia, the Indian sub-continent, all of Africa, and turned South of the Border into Iberia West.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>All that plus turning the Indian Ocean and the south pacific peoples into Euro-like countries, vide Hawaii, Guam, the French Islands, not to mention Australia and New Zealand. Even the USA began as part of that Euro project.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>We Americans thrust our military power all over the world, but, unlike the European colonialists who exploited others and grew rich. We exploit our own taxpayers to pay for the mightiest military in history.&nbsp;When we sent the jobs of our white workers to the lands of brown peoples who demanded less pay, we exacerbated the white folk\'s&nbsp;sense of having been demoted. Now they\'re angry. Browns will soon vote in numbers that threaten \"White Supremacy.\"&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I just read that the 500,000,000 brown peoples of India, a former Brit colony, &nbsp;will soon get free medical care.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>We&rsquo;re told that&nbsp;we \"can&rsquo;t afford&rdquo; to care for ours, white or brown.<br /><br />Does that mean the hyper wealthy of the USA are colonizing? ...ruling? ...dominating? &nbsp;the rest of the USA?&nbsp;<br /><br />Maybe. What\'s wrong with us? Why don\'t we turn our fury into a determination to adapt?</p>\r\n<p>The story of human history has been to adapt. For tens of thousands of years, humans adapted to everything nature hurled at us and&nbsp;we survived everywhere. Now we angry whites sulk and refuse to adapt to change.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; <br /><br /></span>The streets of Miami are covered with salt water and we cling in futile anger to the lifeboats of our sinking Titanic. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>'),
(50, '2019-03-23', 'Say \"CONTROL,\"  forget legalize', '', 'Stop talking about &ldquo;legalizing&rdquo; marijuana. Define the issue as the need to control hemp in all its forms. To be precise, the cultural issue we have clouded, not been transparent about, is the control of THC. We have fought against the use of that substance since 1937, without ever saying so. <br /><br />But now, the growth of the cannabidiol industry has finally weakened the grip of those who fear the &ldquo;high&rdquo; produced by THC, with the result that millions are discovering we have pain killing agents in both CBD and THC of immense power with none of the horrible side effects of opioids. <br /><br />And hemp is not held in the grip of Big Pharma. That is to the good. I am for the growth of the CBD - Hemp industry. I hope it skyrockets under a sane and fair protocol. Furthermore, I hope hemp does not become dominated bv the drug/medical industry. <br /><br />Let&rsquo;s take control of the substance as we do with alcohol and tobacco. For years data has shown how prohibition failed. Let&rsquo;s admit it and move on. We&rsquo;ll save lives, weaken criminality, and increase government budgets with new taxes on hemp users. Let our police concentrate on killer substances like the opioids and meth.'),
(51, '2019-04-03', 'I Surrender to Zero and One', '', 'I surrender. I surrender to the digital world, the world of zero and one, of 0 and 1, of logarithms and equations. I am of the typewriter generation. If, on this day in 2019, the digital world of WWW and HTTPS is about 30 years old, I was one retired old monkey when it started. I had an IBM typewriter on my desk and thought of myself as king of the technical mountain. <br /><br />Now? I surrender. It seems that everyday, the digital world, the world of links and apps and programs and hacks gets more complicated, more challenging, even more threatening. And on those days, I expect from a bank or a site of importance, another damned note telling me of changes that I must take care of immediately or suffer the consequences to life and treasure. Well, maybe only to treasure. <br /><br />I don&rsquo;t recall that kind of interference in my life back in the typewriter generation. Business used to leave us alone. Now it&rsquo;s all about security. And I should complain about that? No. And Yes. I should. If you want to serve for a price, serve without demands. <br /><br />Solve the problems with out demanding more from your customers. <br /><br />If it were not for my grandson (who designed and built this website - Thank you Sean) and who lives in the Netherlands and who takes over my computer with an app called TeamViewer, I&rsquo;d need a local computer craftsman like an electrician or a plumber to come to the house and solve my daily problems. &hellip; usually with one click.<br /><br />Enough, I feel like I&rsquo;m living in the world of the Model T, where back in the thirties, Uncle Gene used to crank the engine to get it started. No job for little kids and nobody liked cranking, so techie wizards solved the problem. Where are you today, Techie Wizards? Get creative. Frustrate hackers.'),
(52, '2019-05-02', 'What does it mean \"to forgive\"?', '', 'In my experience, and I find this especially true of the media, the words &ldquo;to forgive&rdquo; most often mean &ldquo;to pardon or absolve,&rdquo; but for centuries it has also meant &ldquo;to let go of,&rdquo; which is the sense I prefer. <br /><br />To let go of one&rsquo;s anger, one&rsquo;s need for revenge, is the healthier choice. Letting go of the need to revenge, relieves victims of negative feelings that damage them, cause them to prolong their suffering. Moreover, we cannot forgive in the sense of absolve; our choice is only to let go and demand atonement or seek revenge. <br /><br />Yesterday there was a state killing (an execution) in Texas; the perpetrator had dragged a man to death. It&rsquo;s reported he wrote these last words, &ldquo;Capital Punishment: with capital, no punishment.&rdquo; That comes from an impenitent man who took no responsibility for his deed. A more effective punishment would require perpetrators to live out their lives alone, with only their own conscience. <br /><br />In my view, at the moment of death, the light of consciousness goes out. And then? Nothing. No memory. No suffering. No expiation. Only obliteration. Thus, death does not punish; it terminates consciousness. We need to find a better way to demand compensation from murderers. <br /><br />We ought base that search in the fact that no matter how repellent murderers may be, they are fellow human beings who have ruined their own lives as well as their victims. To do our best we need to empathize with that fact. <br /><br />By the way, the family of the Texas victim pleaded that the killer&rsquo;s life be spared, a sign of their emotional and thoughtful maturity. <br /><br />In any case, to let go of the need for revenge is for our own good.'),
(53, '2019-05-01', 'Gaia\'s Child, or the critter who evolved to become the universe aware of itself', '', 'In a NY Times article entitled \"The Earth is Just as Alive as You Are,\" published on 4/20/19, Ferris Jabr writes about Gaia, the Earth, being a living thing. He makes an excellent argument that Earth is alive because of all the life and life supporting things blooming and churning upon it. In the course of his piece, Jabr says &ldquo;We [humans] are Earth made aware of itself.&rdquo; I&rsquo;ve been saying for years that we are the universe aware of itself, but too often when I say that I&rsquo;m met with dead eyes in response. It is so obvious. <br /><br />No other creature seems able to know the universe as we do. I can&rsquo;t imagine smart elephants, or orcas, or Border Collies telling each other about Black Holes. We are unique as the Earth made aware of itself, and that tells me we have a responsibility to take care of our Mother Earth, as well as our DNA cousins, all other life.<br /><br />This immense caring role we have been given as children of Earth and Universe reminds me of our concept of God that Michelangelo painted on the ceiling of the Sistine Chapel. It is a fine image of a robust old man, of us, actually. And we, of the Patriarchal traditions, apply to that image an assumption that the Great Universe Spirit also thinks like us; decides this, makes that, and wants something else. We and Michelangelo imagine that God&rsquo;s like us. <br /><br />There&rsquo;s another way. Imagine the Great Spirit of the Universe (GSU) clicked \"Start\" to get the universe started, and then let its incredible tool, evolution, takeover the process of turning energy into matter and matter into babies, orca babies, or Border Collie babies, or human babies, or oak seeds, and all other life. There&rsquo;s nothing more amazing. <br /><br />See the universe as a singular work of art given us by the GSU. See it evolve to becoming self-aware in a critter that emerged from its own rocks! Us! Ongelooflijk! <br /><br />And now that critter -us- is working to create software that after we click &ldquo;Start&rdquo; evolves into making ever better and stronger and more mysterious results without our governing the process. Like the GSU! <br /><br />Isn&rsquo;t that an attempt to make software evolve from scratch the way GSU coded the universe? From this point of view, we are trying to be like GSU instead of imagining it to be like us. Hopefully, the Great Software will evolve ways to make sure we take care of Earth and its children. <br /><br />I&rsquo;m afraid though, that we&rsquo;ll be happy with software that acts like us, like a Michelangelo character.'),
(55, '2019-06-01', 'Take a half hour with George Will', '', '<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">Give yourself a gift. &nbsp;Watch this interview with George Will for 36 minutes. &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<a class=\"\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eR4RCBBW27k\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eR4RCBBW27k</a></div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">He is the friendly, incisive, thoughtful, learned, conservative I&rsquo;d most like to have dinner with. &nbsp;We would disagree on a lot, but we would not disagree on the fact that the presidency has become monstrous, excessively powerful, and a threat. &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">And I would give a lot of thought to his premise that when Congress makes a lot of laws, they are just offering sentiments, leaving the power of the real law making to unelected bureaucrats whose decisions control our lives. &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">I also like what he has to say about factions and the need for fluid interactions among them, something that we&rsquo;ve lost in the last couple &nbsp;decades. &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">But he has much more to say that gives a sharper edge to my progressive point of view, thus demonstrating again that the debate between the conservative and the progressive is embodied in our DNA. &nbsp;That, by the way, makes us so sure of our righteousness that we become capable of going too far with our predilections if given the power to do so. &nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"Apple-Mail-URLShareUserContentTopClass\">I&rsquo;ve thought for a long time that the success of the conservative reaction we are living with began with Reagan, and that it happened because progressives went too far and the body politic could stand no more change in that direction. &nbsp;Now that seems to be happening to conservative thinking.</div>'),
(56, '2019-06-14', 'The Supper', '', 'Real history: &nbsp;(Or the perspective of a guy who&rsquo;s been living exclusively with women for 65 years:) <br /><br />Headline The Guardian: CHILE BISHOP RESIGNS AFTER SUGGESTING THERE IS A REASON THE LAST SUPPER HAD NO WOMEN <br /><br />So, the bishop says that when the boys gathered for dinner, Jesus told the girls to stay in the back room. &nbsp;Yes!&nbsp; <br /><br />And they did. They&rsquo;d had enough. &nbsp;The guys exploited them, didn&rsquo;t want get married, and who would want to marry them anyway? &nbsp;They were all stuck on a man who washed their feet. &nbsp;Weird. What&rsquo;d he do that for? &nbsp; <br /><br />And you had to fix meals, wash their dirty PJs in the river, serve, clean up. \"Enough already, the back room&rsquo;s good. &nbsp;We&rsquo;ll play bridge. &nbsp;Or Mexican Train. Who needs &lsquo;em? &nbsp;Let&rsquo;s go over to Goldberg&rsquo;s and get a bottle.&rdquo; <br /><br />https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jun/15/chile-bishop-resigns-after-suggesting-there-is-a-reason-the-last-supper-had-no-women?utm_term=RWRpdG9yaWFsX0d1YXJkaWFuVG9kYXlVUy0xOTA2MTU%3D&amp;utm_source=esp&amp;utm_medium=Email&amp;utm_campaign=GuardianTodayUS&amp;CMP=GTUS_email'),
(57, '2019-06-23', 'The MADNESS Within Us', '', 'Ok, here it is. You knew it had to happen. Almost 2020, and we&rsquo;re in a new arms race with Russia, China, and whoever has the money. Check it out: <a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/19/magazine/hypersonic-missiles.html?action=click&amp;module=Well&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;section=The%20New%20York%20Times%20Magazine\">https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/19/magazine/hypersonic-missiles.html?action=click&amp;module=Well&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;section=The%20New%20York%20Times%20Magazine </a><br /><br />We are talking about human madness, a deep inability - perhaps located in our DNA - to trust. And, prepared to destroy civilization, we&rsquo;ll defend that to the death. <br /><br />We are a paradox, preachers of peace, and wielder of weapons, always pitching the rationale that we must protect ourselves against the OTHER. <br /><br />We talk peace, but - innately ferocious - we will attack. We project on the other what we know about ourselves, that we cannot trust. When we spend the money, we always rationalize with talk of defense. Department of Defense. <br /><br />We are Mad to the bone. Mutual Assured Destruction. At least we and the Soviet were honest about that. Maybe I&rsquo;m wrong. Maybe the paradox isn&rsquo;t wired in. Maybe in evolutionary terms we&rsquo;re a little better than chimps evolving to become adolescent. Maybe a time will come when we grow some wisdom and trust negotiation to work. Not soon. Can&rsquo;t trust. <br /><br />The attack will come soon. Gotta believe it. The Iranians thought maybe not &hellip; until two days ago. Now they know they must get nukes and defend themselves against their OTHER, us. North Korea can provide. <br /><br />Back in the Sixties, the great writer, Peter Matthiessen, wrote a book entitled Under the Mountain Wall, about primitive people in New Guinea. The peaceful tribe on one side of the hill could not trust the peaceful tribe on the other side of the hill. Every so often, the peaceful warriors from the East would appear on the hill - surely for some good defensive reason - armed with spears to attack. The peaceful tribe from the West had to defend. So, their warriors (humans always have an MOS called &ldquo;warriors&rdquo; or &ldquo;heros&rdquo;) came out with their spears and both sides hurled weapons at each other &rsquo;til a warrior got hurt. One blooding was enough. Women and children were spared. Warriors made peace. <br /><br />The madness was in them, but it is worse in us. We have lost the respect they had for the sacredness of women and children. That is who we are. <br /><br />So, suck it up. Lock and Load. Time for a drink. But don&rsquo;t dare take a toke. That&rsquo;ll make your heros into peace lovers who&rsquo;d rather go home to Ithaca and snuggle with Penelope.'),
(58, '2019-07-27', 'In the Oval Office, a short play', '', '<p>IN THE OVAL OFFICE he sits at his desk. She stands next to him looking down toward him. He looks straight ahead. The words spoken are the exact words spoken by the two people, which is why they are in quotes.</p>\r\n<p>Characters: The President of the United States about 73<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Nadia Murad, about 25, a Yazidi woman who was raped.</p>\r\n<p>She: &ldquo;Sir, We cannot go back if we cannot protect our dignity, our family&rdquo;.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; </span>(He looks straight ahead)<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>She: &ldquo;They killed my mom, my six brothers,&rdquo;<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</span>(He looks toward her)<br />He: <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>&ldquo;Where are they now?&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>She:<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>&ldquo;They are in the mass graves in Sinjar,&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>He:<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; &nbsp; </span>&ldquo;I know the area very well, you&rsquo;re talking about. It&rsquo;s tough. And you got a Nobel Prize. &nbsp;That&rsquo;s incredible. They gave&nbsp;it to you for what reason?&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>She: <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>&ldquo;For what reason? I made it clear to everyone that ISIS raped thousands of Yazidi women,&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>He:<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; &nbsp; </span>&ldquo;Oh really? Is that right?&rdquo;<br /><br /><br /></p>'),
(59, '2019-08-01', 'Make E Pluribus Unum our sacred reality again', '', '<p>Recent revelations of white contempt for African Americans by Nixon and Reagan uncover another example of how much ugliness has been living and reproducing under the rocks of our culture. Hidden, until recently, in the same way we&rsquo;ve hidden and nurtured sexual abuse as exemplified by the priest and pastor scandals and the big shot gropers, it all shows a deep adolescent refusal to take responsibility for our behavior.</p>\r\n<p>I recall the cultural contentment of the pre-Viet Nam fifties, when the national consensus was &ldquo;all&rsquo;s right with the world, we won, we&rsquo;ll lead the way to heaven.&rdquo;<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Right. We led to so much change that tens of millions couldn&rsquo;t handle it, then came conservative reaction and the discontentment we&rsquo;re living in.</p>\r\n<p>And what do the debating Democrat candidates of the last weeks reveal?<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>A lot of mediocre good guys.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>A little passion (Warren and Bernie), less wisdom.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>And a lot of conviction and fear that the Right Wing Conservatives are correct; &ldquo;don&rsquo;t go too far left or Trumpism will win.&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>Please, Good Guys, chill, fix the roads, rebuild bridges, &amp; rediscover E Pluribus Unum.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>'),
(60, '2019-08-30', 'Domestic bullying', '', 'The New Yorker published a piece in the 8/19 issue entitled &ldquo;A House of Their Own&rdquo; by Larissa MacFarquhar, in which she details efforts by battered women in Boston to provide places for battered women to escape to. <br /><br />Interestingly, the piece provides no reason for domestic abuse.It explores many possibilities, but comes to no conclusion. From my pov the primary reason is bullying. <br /><br />I am the father of two daughters, Alexandra and Amelia. Marty and I have been married for over 63 years. There were times in those 63 years when I got very angry and even raised my fist at her. It never went any further because she always came back at me like a tiger and her fury always stopped me. She showed her power. <br /><br />It worked and we taught the kids to do the same thing. Let the tiger out. <br /><br />Both of them have been married for 20 years and more. I&rsquo;ve seen no sign of beatings. Maybe they\'ve let the tiger out from time to time. To put it differently, the women in my family know it is ok to demonstrate their personal power, their rage. <br /><br />While reading &ldquo;A House of Their Own,&rdquo; I kept thinking &ldquo;battering isn&rsquo;t mysterious. It is about \'hen pecking.\'&rdquo; Yea. Bad word, I know. Bullying - strong chickens pecking weaker chickens - is a better description. Or bullying in schools. Or bullying in marriages. <br /><br />To me \"domestic violence\" is a weak, abstract usage. The battering issue in the home is about power and letting the bully - man or woman, mother or father - get away with it because of fears of all the things that could happen that may be worse than the beatings. &ldquo;A House of Their Own&rdquo; implies as much. <br /><br />I wonder what would happen if women in places like places for battered women to escape to were taught how - and encouraged - to let the tiger out come what may!'),
(61, '2019-09-03', 'On NOT giving your life to a career', '', 'I\'ve never liked the cultural dominance of the idea that we should give our lives to a career. <br /><br />When I was twenty-five and newly married, I liked the idea of teaching because it was rewarding and supported my family and gave me 3 summer months to spend with them. After while I also found that I could develop other talents in those summer months. I did. I wrote. Developed skills as a wood carver, learned how to do a lot of do-it-youself around the house, even got better at parenting, maybe became a better lover. <br /><br />Living the good life became my objective. My wife also had talents she wanted to develop, and soon found herself working as an independent interpersonal consultant making good money. She hadn\'t thought about that before. She discovered it and thrived. <br /><br />Our daughters followed our paths in their own ways and thrived, playing and developing their talents. Both had adventures as Green Peace Activists. Today they live in loving marriages that work. They know how to handle conflict in creative and thoughtful ways. They chose men who follow similar paths that place making life good their first objective. <br /><br />We all have enough income to buy what we want with more left over. We are content. I\'m nearly 90, working with one of those talents I developed. It has proven to be a good thing to live a good life. Lucky us. How about devoting yourself to developing a good life? Would you call that a career?'),
(62, '2020-02-08', 'Media Editors want to make us feel jumpy', '', 'Think about editorial decisions taken by the media. The political stories told over the last three years reveal that the exaggerators are on both sides. Nothing new in that. <br /><br />But the Corona virus stories seem to make balloons out of comparatively small facts. For example, compare Coronavirus stories with influenza facts that&ndash;&ndash;like traffic deaths&ndash;&ndash;are almost forgotten in pop media.<br /><br />We know the media scare us into buying baloney. Coronavirus now leads. It used to be Trump. Before that it was &ldquo;if it bleeds it leads,&rdquo; now if they vomit, bomb it. <br /><br />The headlines are all China. OVER 900 HAVE DIED. I won&rsquo;t argue. That sounds bad.<br /><br />At the same time the influenza virus is killing up to 50,000&ndash;&ndash;see this CDC link__ a year and the media seem comfy with that; no need to tell the people. <a href=\"https://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/burden/index.html\">https://www.cdc.gov/flu/about/burden/index.html</a><br /><br />Like Traffic deaths. You&rsquo;ve got to do research to find the data. \"The NSC estimates that in 2018, 40,000 people died in car crashes&mdash;a 1 percent decline from 40,231 deaths in 2017 and 40,327 deaths in 2016.&rdquo; <a href=\"https://ohsonline.com/articles/2019/02/18/nsc-motor-vehicle-deaths.aspx\">https://ohsonline.com/articles/2019/02/18/nsc-motor-vehicle-deaths.aspx</a>. &nbsp;Cheers! 200 fewer. No headline there.<br /><br />Add &lsquo;em up: 40K flu + 50K crashes- We&rsquo;re killing off a lot of our people, but it&rsquo;s normal. The sun comes up, goes down. The seasons change. No headlines <br /><br />But are the facts given/not given worth contemplating? Don&rsquo;t they signal something about our values? What civilization means to us? The risks we take, the prices we pay, and why??<br /><br />Stories succeed on the basis of their emotional impact.'),
(63, '2020-02-23', 'Lets Think About the Way We Educate Children', '', 'As one who has played in the game of education all my life, I wish people could begin to think about professionalizing teaching, not licensing. We license plumbers and electricians. <br /><br />I&rsquo;m talking about professionalizing teachers on the level of lawyers and physicians. Remove teachers from labor unions too. Unions are wrong for professionals. Teachers need to be part of professional organizations like professors and doctors and members of the bar to qualify and guarantee that they earn six-figure salaries. Professional associations serve the interests of the public as well as members to establish values, standards, and the quality of colleagues. Think levels of professional preparation including interns, assistants, and master teachers. <br /><br />Our kids are our most valuable renewable source and treasure, yet we treat their education with something close to disdain, as though they are unworthy of a full investment in their young lives and the preparations of the teachers responsible for their development. Strangely, we blame children for not liking school when school systems and teachers are the problems the children must endure. It&rsquo;s like being made to drink castor oil because it&rsquo;s good for you. <br /><br />Why should our investment in human learning on the level of elementary and secondary be any different from learning in graduate schools or post-docs where we invest almost without hesitation? Because the attitudes governing the culture toward schooling are left-over attitudes from the 19th century when we believed we had to train people to run lathes and locomotives and operate typewriters. That no longer works; the schools need to serve another objective. <br /><br />Young people of the 21st century must be inculcated with a love of learning that drives them to learn continually for a lifetime. And that is not about passing tests, a small aspect of what students need to do. Instill the joy of learning and demonstrating mastery becomes an everyday part of the joyful process and the satisfaction that comes with learning. <br /><br />We must bring teachers and parents together in schools. Let&rsquo;s have periodic luncheons or informal coffee meetings where parents, mentors, and children join to assess progress and concerns. Again, use professionals like physicians and lawyers as a model. Experiment with new ways of preparing teachers, with school days that are different. Let the Federal Department of Education offer grants to teachers and schools to enable specific experiments in learning. <br /><br />Make project-centered learning with mentors the primary method, which is exactly what humans did for ten thousand years. Our ancestors apprenticed young people to masters of crafts. Then we began the current crumbling public schooling system we&rsquo;ve clung to since about 1850. <br /><br />It&rsquo;s time to think and re-evaluate the entire system.'),
(64, '2020-03-14', 'The depth of mysogyny in western culture', '', 'I\'ve encountered several uses of the word &ldquo;gaslighting&rdquo; in the media recently. It&rsquo;s become a journalist&rsquo;s cliche`, but I couldn\'t quite grasp the way it was being used, so I went to the source, the 1944 film Gaslight , directed by George Cukor with Charles Boyer, Ingrid Bergman, and Joseph Cotten in the leading roles. (There&rsquo;ve been other re-makes, but Cukor&rsquo;s remains the most referenced.) <br /><br />The story defines misogyny. But our journalists don&rsquo;t use the word &ldquo;gaslighting&rdquo; in that sense, but in a more general sense of manipulating a person&rsquo;s thinking to undermine their values. But Gaslight&rsquo;s primary theme focuses on a male dominating a female until she believes she is crazy. She makes herself vulnerable to him and he sees that opening and makes her his slave. He destroys her independent sense of self. <br /><br />Were the character played by a black actress, the idea would be clear: she is a slave. The female lead&ndash;Bergman&ndash;is driven into a trembling shell of herself until she is saved by a man&ndash;the Cotton character, a detective. It is fair, then to infer that George Cukor&rsquo;s essential driving idea behind the film&ndash;and the play that proceeded it in 1940&ndash;is that the female is the weaker, easily dominated human being, who is saved from herself only by the intervention of a good man. <br /><br />BUT, if one goes back to look at reviews of Gaslight, those deep cultural themes don&rsquo;t get picked up by reviewers! They talk about everything else, but it is as if reviewers of Gaslight then and now are blind to the cultural depth of the misogyny in that story. If I&rsquo;m right about that blindness in professional reviewers then and now, then the depth of our cultural expectations about male/female domination and submission has only been scratched on its surface. <br /><br />Thus when people think of misogyny as hate&ndash;&ndash;which Webster&rsquo;s dictionary does&ndash;&ndash; they miss the deeper point. Misogyny is more about contempt or disdain and leads to slave-making, domineering, controlling and has been with us at least since the classic Greeks. Or even before that given the spread of Indo-European warrior tribes and the patriarchal successes in the middle east. I was first brought to this kind of thinking by Marija Gimbutas&rsquo; book The Goddesses and Gods of Old Europe back in the 70s. <a href=\"https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-06-11-tm-2975-story.html.\">https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-1989-06-11-tm-2975-story.html. </a><br /><br />She was an archeologist. Her book was much dismissed at first. One shouldn&rsquo;t be surprised because she describes cultures that were not male-dominated, if anything, the genders collaborated. By the way, what is the animal most despised in the Patriarchal cultures? Pigs, statues of which Gimbutas found all over the remains of cultures she studied, cultures that later came to be dominated by the patriarchs who made pigs the symbol of bad. And they still are.');
