(66, '2020-04-26', 'Galileo to Hubble and Now', '', '<br />The Great Astronomical Debate. Herewith one unimpressive b&amp;w photo and one paragraph:<br /><br /><a href=\"https://apod.nasa.gov/apod/ap200426.html\">https://apod.nasa.gov/apod/ap200426.html</a><br /><br />Check it out. Until only 100 years ago today, human beings and many astronomers believed the Milky Way was the entire universe. There was no other galaxy, and not a glimpse or thought of a Big Bang, Black Holes, billions of other galaxies, or exo-planets. <br /><br />No one knew that the materials that make our bodies&ndash;&ndash;atoms and molecules&ndash;&ndash;had been cooked into being in the belly of a star.<br /><br />We have lived through an age of Discovery.'),
(67, '2020-04-27', 'The Webb telescope: First the Big Bang, then stars, then us.', '', 'it&rsquo;s only been a hundred years that cosmology has moved from theory to testable science and it was Hubble who started the discoveries some people out there now take for granted. Check this list for pictures from the Hubble telescope: <br /><a href=\"https://aviationweek.com/shows-events/space-symposium/hubble-space-telescope-highlights-over-years?utm_rid=CPEN1000001792698&amp;utm_campaign=23859&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;elq2=7336a8c28cdf4aa5afd1a461f784614e\">https://aviationweek.com/shows-events/space-symposium/hubble-space-telescope-highlights-over-years?utm_rid=CPEN1000001792698&amp;utm_campaign=23859&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;elq2=7336a8c28cdf4aa5afd1a461f784614e</a><br /><br />And check out <a href=\"https://apod.nasa.gov/apod/astropix.html\">https://apod.nasa.gov/apod/astropix.html</a><br />And be sure to scroll down and check on the archive.<br /><br />And if you really get the bug read about the new Webb telescope. <a href=\"https://www.jwst.nasa.gov/\">https://www.jwst.nasa.gov/</a><br />Fantastic knowledge our grandfathers could not imagine.<br /><br />The Hubble telescope up there now has a mirror/lens about 8 feet in diameter. The new Webb telescope lens will have a mirror/lens about 21 feet in diameter orbiting the sun about 950,000 miles from Earth, a transformational technology only a hundred years after Hubble discovered our Milky Way was not the entire universe. They are hoping the new Webb (to go up next year) will take us back in time to the Big Bang era. <br /><br />There was the Big Bang, some time passed, stars formed, then there was us.'),
(68, '2020-04-29', 'Life and consciousness as attributes of evolution', '', 'I&rsquo;ve been reading a lot about the ways people have been trying to approach the study of consciousness even to the most recent notion that it can be examined mathematically.<br /><br />I don&rsquo;t know how to approach the problem from a scientist&rsquo;s pov or from a philosopher&rsquo;s. I think of consciousness as part of evolution, that the evolutionary process allows certain materials to combine in certain ways to produce life. Not just animals, but plants as well, and perhaps even fungi. <br /><br />And life forms do things. That implies consciousness to me.<br /><br />I am emphatically not talking about panpsychism, which implies &ndash;&ndash;or allow us to infer&ndash;&ndash;intentionality which is not needed when thinking about consciousness. Panpsychism is more about some kind of oversoul. Nay.<br /><br />The idea we all accept is that chemistry evolves to life and life is conscious. Not intentional. Not progressive. Just another possibility of the process that began with the big bang developed stars, and stardust - me and my plants.<br /><br />We know the chemistry of trees allows trees to communicate with each other in certain situations, that plants have relationships with one another and sometimes with fungi as well. I can&rsquo;t site sources, forgive me, but they are out there.<br /><br />The idea I&rsquo;m playing with, as a writer, has nothing to do with an intentional universe or materialism as panpsychism is often imagined, no mystic superstition here. I&rsquo;m a pure materialist who sees life as part of Evolution on Earth. AND if it happens here, why not other places?<br /><br />My plants, btw, know when to send new leaves out of their twigs in the Spring and when to blossom and when to go to sleep again. It&rsquo;s chemistry at bottom. Some bacteria eat viruses. And viruses know how to connect with my cells to reproduce. Is that NOT a species of consciousness? <br /><br />To think that the universe is planned and intentional seems unnecessary and without evidence. No one has ever produced evidence that can be tested of a universal mind or of anything beyond our universe. <br /><br />But we live with life every day and in my experience, it is all conscious to some degree.<br /><br />Consciousness is an attribute of life, which is an attribute of chemical evolution and there is no other kind. <br /><br />We seem to have lots of evidence for that idea, so what is wrong with it?'),
(69, '2020-05-11', 'Bill Barr and the Boss', '', 'The present White House is surely not a source of criminal behavior, but it has all the aspects of a criminal organization. <br /><br />Our WH is led by the Boss, his Captains, and his Made Men, fronted by Pretty Females twisting reality like pole dancers. And all of it is given legal cover by the Consiglieri, the Boss\'s confidant, the adviser who Passes in the world like a true professional, but who is driven because he finds his needs fulfilled by his ability to serve Power. Why will so many abandon their values to keep this going?'),
(70, '2020-05-12', 'We have to learn to live with covid-19', '', '<p>Today is May 8th, 2020. The headline on our local paper, The Journal, tells us &ldquo;Everybody&rsquo;s Ready to Get Out, Restaurants open doors&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>I&rsquo;m sure many are &ldquo;ready&rdquo; to get out. I saw 4 young people standing on the street corner yesterday.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>They were physically close&ndash;&ndash;within arm&rsquo;s distance&ndash;&ndash;and chatting.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Unmasked.</p>\r\n<p>We just came from the liquor store in Seneca.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>I sat in the car, Marty went in.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>She was Masked.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Six other people went in and came out.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>None wore masks.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Marty reported that the clerk wore no mask either but, \"sprayed everything.&rdquo; Ok. So far, a lot of people are &ldquo;ready.&rdquo; That&rsquo;s understandable, and, I think, reasonable if smart precautions are taken.</p>\r\n<p>Many will disagree with me.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>I&rsquo;ve heard some say they won&rsquo;t come out until vaccinated.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Others choose to return to old habits m asap, and take their chances.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>I believe the better way is go out with care.</p>\r\n<p>I think we all need to develop a different attitude about how to deal with this pandemic.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Too many are scared. For some it is as if we were living through the Black Plague, which tortured and killed 1/3 to 1/2 the population of Europe. They poor souls had no knowledge about the disease. It&rsquo;s still around, by the way.</p>\r\n<p>Or, if you want grisly horror served up in English, read A Journal of the Plague Year by Daniel Defoe.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>It&rsquo;s<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>about the plague that hit London in 1665. First published in March 1722, it has never been out of print. (The London government of 1665 sounds Trump.)</p>\r\n<p>My point is that we humans have lived through these killing diseases for all of our history, and even as recently as 1968. The last bad flu epidemic happened in 1968!<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>A million or more were killed worldwide in 1968.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>The Britannica \"estimated one million to four million deaths&rdquo;<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>According to Google, the first flu vaccine was available &ldquo;by the 1940s after the influenza virus was first discovered in the early 1930s. Soldiers fighting in World War II were the first patients to receive the flu vaccine when it was approved for military use in 1945 and civilian use was approved the following year.&rdquo; <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Marty and I were in our thirties or forties when we got our first flu vaccine.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>We had managed. and learned how to live with flu, AND, I<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>got pneumonia with flu in about 1970 and survived. Get a shot.</p>\r\n<p>I also learned how to live with polio when I was a kid. That disease is now Out of sight out of mind. Our President had polio, another virus; see The March of Dimes.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>We were all terrified. &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t go swimming, kids!&rdquo; A lot of us went swimming anyway, but we were conscious of the threat, and mostly tried to do the right thing. Yet, My aunt had polio. It is still a threat in some countries.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Polio was known to the ancient Egyptians.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>From Google: &ldquo; By 1910, frequent epidemics became regular events&hellip; during the summer months. At its peak in the 1940s and 1950s, polio would paralyze or kill over half a million people worldwide every year.</p>\r\n<p><span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>\"On Saturday, June 17, 1916, an official announcement of the existence of an epidemic polio infection was made in Brooklyn, New York. That year, there were over 27,000 cases and more than 6,000 deaths due to polio in the United States, with over 2,000 deaths in New York City alone.[15] &ldquo;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_polio</p>\r\n<p>Polio vaccine was not developed until 1954, two years before we got married. \"On February 23, 1954, a group of children from Arsenal Elementary School in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, receive the first injections of the new polio vaccine developed by Dr. Jonas Salk.&rdquo;<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>We have to learn to live with covid. We have always lived our ordinary every day lives with danger. We can live with danger, and I believe we need to better balance our attitude. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>We cannot become hermits until a vaccine gets developed.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Our people don\'t know about bad today because we&rsquo;ve been protected from bad in our lifetime. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>We came out of our huts<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>and learned how to take care of our selves. We are living with mortal danger now but with the flu!<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>The Covid fear has cowed us. But flu has not. Half do not believe in flu vaccine.</p>\r\n<p>&ldquo; This season CDC (2019-2020) estimates [are] that, as of mid-March (2020), between 29,000 and 59,000 [will] have died due to influenza illnesses&hellip;&rdquo;</p>\r\n<p>In spite of danger, we learned how to live with viral disease.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>But today many are living in an on-going panic toay. And the dangers are real.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Yes.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>No argument. The danger is there.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>And we can learn to live with it without living alone is our caves. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>I think the people who went into the liquor store without masks today were selfish, self-indulgent, unwise, and without courtesy. They shopped, and maybe they went home negative.</p>\r\n<p>I hope so.</p>'),
(71, '2020-05-13', 'Of Victor David Hanson and Trump at the University of Pennsylvania', '', '<p>I&rsquo;ve been watching interviews with Victor David Hanson, the author of a historical study I much admire:<em> A War Like No Other</em> (2005) about the Peloponnesian war. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;<br /><br /></span>Hanson is the author of several other studies of military conflict, ancient Greece, and one&ndash;&ndash;<em>Why the West Has Won&ndash;&ndash;</em>in which he argued that the dominance of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Hemisphere\">Western</a>&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_culture\">civilization</a>, beginning with the ancient Greeks, results from certain fundamental aspects of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_Hemisphere\">Western</a>&nbsp;culture, such as consensual government, a tradition of self-critique, secular rationalism, religious tolerance, individual freedom, free expression, free markets, and individualism. See<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span><a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victor_Davis_Hanson\">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victor_Davis_Hanson</a></p>\r\n<p>I agree.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Those are characteristics of the sunny side of Western Culture, but there&rsquo;s also a dark side that includes ruthless subjugation, dominance, cruelty, and a tribal ethos that has no place for empathy.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>We&rsquo;ve not been all good.</p>\r\n<p>Nevertheless,<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>I much appreciate and admire Victor David Hanson&ndash;&ndash;none of us are perfect&ndash;&ndash;not only for his magisterial scholarship and writing but for his restrained and articulate championship of the conservative perspective.</p>\r\n<p>And while I admire him and would love to chat with him&ndash;not debate to win points, but to learn&ndash;&ndash;I disagree with most of his view of life.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>With that in mind,<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>I recommend an interview he participated in.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FEXL5USuDGI\">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FEXL5USuDGI</a></p>\r\n<p>We must encourage conversations like that.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>They are the fuel of democracy.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>And let&rsquo;s choose the best people we can find&ndash;&ndash;like Hanson&ndash;&ndash;to talk with.</p>\r\n<p>He has a new book&ndash;&ndash;<em>The Case for Trump&ndash;&ndash;</em>in which he boosts Trump while seeing all the negativity in the man, but he makes the case that Trump intuitively knows how to connect with people who feel scorned or left out, and that leads to a kind of conservative renaissance.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>I haven&rsquo;t read the book, only read reviews, and listened to Hanson talk about it.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>I think his analysis of what makes Trump a winner, makes sense.</p>\r\n<p>But it does little to justify the cruel&ndash;&ndash;children in cages&ndash;&ndash;self-dealing, apathetic&ndash;&ndash;vs empathic&ndash;&ndash;personality that is Trump.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Hanson seems like a natural-born conservative&ndash;&ndash;which we need&ndash;&ndash;and like many conservatives of his age, he abhors the unleashed liberal forces that since WWWII&ndash;&ndash;in my opinion&ndash;&ndash;have gone too far.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Those forces made deep cultural changes that are intolerable from the traditional White Christian perspective and ethos.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>His opposition makes sense.</p>\r\n<p>But his support of Trump for re-election is a mistake and seems to be the conversation we are now having in the months before November 3d.</p>\r\n<p>I have a small stake in this game. Trump and I over-lapped each other at the University of Pennsylvania in the mid-sixties. He earned a bachelor&rsquo;s degree from the Wharton School of Business in &rsquo;68, and I earned a PhD from the School of Graduate Arts and Sciences in &rsquo;65.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>We never met.</p>\r\n<p>But, as an alum, I find it interesting that while Trump talks up Penn and its much respected school of business, Penn never mentions Trump although he is Penn&rsquo;s first alumnus to become President.</p>\r\n<p>Penn doesn&rsquo;t talk Trump.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Penn has never honored him and the reasons are murky because Penn maintains silence about Trump that is telling. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>You can get the story from<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span><a href=\"https://www.phillymag.com/news/2019/09/14/donald-trump-at-wharton-university-of-pennsylvania/\">https://www.phillymag.com/news/2019/09/14/donald-trump-at-wharton-university-of-pennsylvania/</a></p>\r\n<p>As much as I admire Victor David Hanson for his scholarship and thoughtful writing, I find it hard to justify his support for a man of obvious flaws to lead this country for another four years.</p>'),
(72, '2020-05-17', 'A personal letter to a friend at a bad time', '', '<p>I sent this to an old friend in New York where things have been especially grim recently.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>He sees the USA as a failing country. I&rsquo;m too pessimistic to let myself think that way. Instead, I&rsquo;m thinking about stupidity.</p>\r\n<p>We started by writing about television and how M and I dropped tv about 15 years ago and have found treasures in other places. We believe paying for cable subscription was like going to a store<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>and being handed a cart filled with stuff you don&rsquo;t want and being made to pay for all of it. That is stupid.</p>\r\n<p>That applies to our country. The USA is not failing, we are going through a phase led by stupidity.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>The principal Stupids are self-dealing leaders at all levels whose primary goal is to maintain power for their own profit, and turn back (MAGA?) the liberal/progressive policies of the last half-century. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Will they have gone too far by November?<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>What will happen? The 2018 election permits a bit of hope, if not optimism. And I&rsquo;m not ready to bet the farm on that happy prospect.</p>\r\n<p>But I see a horizon, I&rsquo;m just not sure if it is sunny on the other side. And I see that the odds are on our side to elect Joe.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>I just wish he&rsquo;d get off his ass and show some energy. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>Of Jared and that whole crew? I wish the media would frame the story of the<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>present White House as what it is, a mafioso crew who have only one thing in common: loyalty to the Don.</p>\r\n<p>Everything begins with the Boss, his personal goals, his made men, and pretty girls who twist reality like a gangster&rsquo;s girl friends who twist on poles. Most importantly, they have a consigliere, Bill Barr, who twists their behavior into fantastic legalities. <span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>The Don sees enemies in the FBI, the CIA, and others who protect American rights.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>His enemies have lacked the power to get rid of him, but there will be consequences. That crew of wise-guys should expect FBI-hell to rain on them like exploding volcanos!<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>The evidence has been collected. Their day is coming.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Like, maybe in February 2021?</p>\r\n<p>Can you imagine how the FBI members feel about the way the FBI has been treated by this crew? They, like us, for instance, believe it is a crime to put kids in cages.</p>\r\n<p>We might even start feeling some compassion for this Don and his mobsters.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Who knows?</p>\r\n<p>The biggest challenge to Joe is to lead in smart, wise, and intelligent ways that bring us together. Then fundamental American values will remerge to guide us. We&rsquo;re not failing.</p>\r\n<p>So, warmest best cosmic good wishes, Dear New Yorker.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Dump your subscriptions and get out the Vote.</p>'),
(73, '2020-05-20', 'On Credulity', '', '<p>For over a month we have put pause to our lives because of the 2020 Covid-19 pandemic.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>For much longer, I have watched another pathology spread across our country, one that took off during the Viet Nam war and has been<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>encouraged by the Right Wing.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>This pathology promotes distrust of government in all of its forms, and it is being encouraged by Trump and his supporters. (Deep State?)</p>\r\n<p>The mistrust has been fueled by a widespread <strong><em>credulousness </em></strong>in the population.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>By that I mean there has developed in the culture a willingness on the part of millions to readily believe what they hear or read on the basis of slight or uncertain evidence.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Or no evidence!</p>\r\n<p>This credulity has been accompanied by a widespread willingness to dismiss science and true expertise.</p>\r\n<p>One sees it in educated people, people who have been trained to think, analyze, and make well-formed judgments.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>Trump&rsquo;s supporters are credulous because they are ready to believe anything he says without demanding he cites evidence for what he says.</p>\r\n<p>Credulity fuels faith in supernatural&ndash;&ndash;religious or simple superstitions&ndash;&ndash; that try to explain nature without evidence.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>There has never in all history been one single piece of evidence set forth about any supernatural claim that can be repeatedly tested.<br /><br />Credulity endangers us.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>In 2019 USA Today reported that hate groups \"climbed to 1,020, up from 784 four years ago, and was propelled by a rise in extremism, the center said. From 2017 to 2018 alone, the tally rose 7 percent. &ldquo;<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>This rise is being fueled by the credulity that supports Trump, his racism, his divisive policies.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>(Fear also helps fuel credulity.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<p>My university training squeezed any tendency to credulity out of me. Anti-vaxxers, for instance, say vaccines used for the public are bad for children. If so, test, demonstrate and display the evidence. Set up an experiment done by a lab that all<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>respect where the vaccines in question get analyzed for all the chemistry in them.<span class=\"Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp; </span>The results will reveal the facts.</p>'),
(74, '2020-06-17', 'Superman Reimagined', '', 'Fascinating evidence of cultural change. Here\'s a new take on Clark Kent, an immigrant with super powers. Get it? In this version&ndash;&ndash;I have not yet read it&ndash;&ndash; he is apparently the enemy of the KKK, a group of white men who try to dominate others. <br /><br />That is a big twist on the idea of Superman, the icon and model&ndash;&ndash;like John Wayne&ndash;&ndash;of American manhood.<br /><br />Moreover, the book is authored and illustrated by Asian Americans. <br /><br /><a href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/2020/06/16/books/review/superman-smashes-klan-gene-lueng-yang.html?action=click&amp;module=Well&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;section=Book%20Review\">https://www.nytimes.com/2020/06/16/books/review/superman-smashes-klan-gene-lueng-yang.html?action=click&amp;module=Well&amp;pgtype=Homepage&amp;section=Book%20Review</a>');

